I'm digging the minor ninth between the bass-line (Solfege: me) and the melody (mi) in the outro music.  It really effectively propels the piece given the less dissonant major ninth (do and re) hear shortly thereafter before resolving stepwise to an octave (do's).  Very nice work.  Suggestion: the piece is very nearly bitonal, which has kind of a nice ring given the accompanying subject material.  Instead of treating the le in the bass as a root position bVI triad with the re in the melody as a passing tone, it might be more effective to treat the le as part of a second inversion iio/ (half-diminished seventh chord).  That way, mi can be heard as an appoggiatura resolving to the root.  Practically, then, it makes sense to treat the bVII like a dominant chord by adding the chordal #11 (mi).  This keeps the tension building and allows for rare moments of unity to stand out that much more.

as an out and out nonbinary person i've decided to switch my label to baltimore-gender after watching this video.  also while i'm here! i do wish this video had touched on gender euphoria. it's something a lot of trans people don't realize that they even experience !! it's ... literally the validation that comes from being correctly gendered. that happy feeling you get when you pass in public, when your waitress calls you 'ma'am', or when you get a casual 'hey girl' from a stranger. and i feel like gender euphoria is cool to know about because being trans isn't about hating yourself every second of every day. it *can* be validating and comforting, despite how badly dysphoria hurts.   and of course plenty of nonbinary people experience dysphoria as well! and do want to medically transition! my partner's cousin mav took an 'androgynizing' dose of hormones, and i'd like to do the same. i'm afab, so i'd like to go on T at some point. and the concept of 'presenting as nonbinary/genderqueer/whatever'--it's exactly like you explained! it can be as simple as stating your gender, or lack thereof, as fact, or it can be performative, just like it can be for binary trans people. for me, i do want top surgery and for my voice to drop, but i still want longish hair and a round face and no facial hair. i do want that societal signal of confusion, but it's still okay if a person just wants to use they/them and that's it, that's their presentation.  anyways sorry for rambling and i know a lot of people might see this as weird, still. i get it, i'm a 19 year old nonbinary person who uses they/them pronouns and not everyone is going to be chill with a weird queer saying weird tumblr things and that's fine  which is why, as i said, i am now baltimore. and if you insult me i will materialize out of the faint swirls of dust swimming in the dim light of your room and pour glitter in your bed so that it becomes rather uncomfortable to sleep and wherein you will continually roll around and get glitter in unflattering areas as a reminder of the fact that it costs $0 to stay in your lane

Originally I was gonna begin this by disagreeing with you, but rather I want to first say the things I agree with you on.   I agree that we shouldn't be assholes to people for no reason. Being mean and insulting others isn't the way to get people to agree with you, discussion is.  Now, discussion is best aided by facts, and this is where I bring up where we disagree. You see researches at stanford have already wondered about the differences in male and female brains. URL  First, on purely psychological differences, 'Women excel in several measures of verbal ability -- pretty much all of them, except for verbal analogies. Women's reading comprehension and writing ability consistently exceed that of men, on average. They outperform men in tests of fine-motor coordination and perceptual speed. They're more adept at retrieving information from long-term memory.  Men, on average, can more easily juggle items in working memory. They have superior visuospatial skills: They're better at visualizing what happens when a complicated two- or three-dimensional shape is rotated in space, at correctly determining angles from the horizontal, at tracking moving objects and at aiming projectiles.  Navigation studies in both humans and rats show that females of both species tend to rely on landmarks, while males more typically rely on 'dead reckoning': calculating one's position by estimating the direction and distance traveled rather than using landmarks.' Straight from the mouths of the researches themselves, literally copy-pasted for better measure rather than quoting from memory.   Now on to actual physical differences, 'The neuroscience literature shows that the human brain is a sex-typed organ with distinct anatomical differences in neural structures and accompanying physiological differences in function, says UC-Irvine professor of neurobiology and behavior Larry Cahill, PhD. Cahill edited the 70-article January/February 2017 issue of the Journal of Neuroscience Research -- the first-ever issue of any neuroscience journal devoted entirely to the influence of sex differences on nervous-system function.  Brain-imaging studies indicate that these differences extend well beyond the strictly reproductive domain, Cahill says. Adjusted for total brain size (men's are bigger), a woman's hippocampus, critical to learning and memorization, is larger than a man's and works differently. Conversely, a man's amygdala, associated with the experiencing of emotions and the recollection of such experiences, is bigger than a woman's. It, too, works differently, as Cahill's research has demonstrated.  In 2000, Cahill scanned the brains of men and women viewing either highly aversive films or emotionally neutral ones. The aversive films were expected to trip off strong negative emotions and concomitant imprinting in the amygdala, an almond-shaped structure found in each brain hemisphere. Activity in the amygdala during the viewing experience, as expected, predicted subjects' later ability to recall the viewed clips. But in women, this relationship was observed only in the left amygdala. In men, it was only in the right amygdala. Cahill and others have since confirmed these results.  Discoveries like this one should ring researchers' alarm buzzers. Women, it's known, retain stronger, more vivid memories of emotional events than men do. They recall emotional memories more quickly, and the ones they recall are richer and more intense. If, as is likely, the amygdala figures into depression or anxiety, any failure to separately analyze men's and women's brains to understand their different susceptibilities to either syndrome would be as self-defeating as not knowing left from right.  The two hemispheres of a woman's brain talk to each other more than a man's do. In a 2014 study, University of Pennsylvania researchers imaged the brains of 428 male and 521 female youths -- an uncharacteristically huge sample -- and found that the females' brains consistently showed more strongly coordinated activity between hemispheres, while the males' brain activity was more tightly coordinated within local brain regions. This finding, a confirmation of results in smaller studies published earlier, tracks closely with others' observations that the corpus callosum--- the white-matter cable that crosses and connects the hemispheres -- is bigger in women than in men and that women's brains tend to be more bilaterally symmetrical than men's.'  There's a ton more interesting stuff like that. However, I'm also one to know that there's no one size fits all human body. Whew biology is a fuck and the human mind is a bigger fuck because it doesn't even need a reason sometimes to just do what it wants. Aided again by our wonderful researchers! 'A 2017 study in JAMA Psychiatry imaged the brains of 98 individuals ages 8 to 22 with autism spectrum disorder and 98 control subjects. Both groups contained roughly equal numbers of male and female subjects. The study confirmed earlier research showing that the pattern of variation in the thickness of the brain's cortex differed between males and females. But the great majority of female subjects with ASD, the researchers found, had cortical-thickness variation profiles similar to those of typical non-ASD males.  In other words, having a typical male brain structure, whether you're a boy or a girl, is a substantial risk factor for ASD. By definition, more boys' than girls' brains have this profile, possibly helping explain ASD's four- to fivefold preponderance among boys compared with girls.'   And furtherly, 'Infant girls respond more readily to faces and begin talking earlier. Boys react earlier in infancy to experimentally induced perceptual discrepancies in their visual environment. In adulthood, women remain more oriented to faces, men to things.  All these measured differences are averages derived from pooling widely varying individual results. While statistically significant, the differences tend not to be gigantic. They are most noticeable at the extremes of a bell curve, rather than in the middle, where most people cluster. Some argue that we may safely ignore them.  But the long list of behavioral tendencies in which male-female ratios are unbalanced extends to cognitive and neuropsychiatric disorders. Women are twice as likely as men to experience clinical depression in their lifetimes; likewise for post-traumatic stress disorder. Men are twice as likely to become alcoholic or drug-dependent, and 40 percent more likely to develop schizophrenia. Boys' dyslexia rate is perhaps 10 times that of girls, and they're four or five times as likely to get a diagnosis of autism spectrum disorder.'   Now on like nonbinary folk I am skeptical but I can not only understand the feeling somewhat but see more than one way it could come about.   'Gerber Dysphoria'  is caused by the brain being the shape of the opposite sex, which then could lead to a more severe form of the brain being perfectly in the middle, or somewhere within a spectrum.   Thing about human biology is it loves its sliding scales. There's patterns everywhere in humans  displaying this, so who's to say gender dysphoria couldn't be something that exists on one too?  And I don't know about others but I try to be nice unless slighted because who wants all that negativity?   I can already tell we may disagree on a lot, but that's all the better saying that it'd be a shame to pass up the opportunity to listen to someone who disagrees with you put up a good point.

Like all values and identities at their foundation, aren't the very concepts of validity and gender arbitrary? In order to convince someone of arbitrary things, they must be shown to conform somehow to that persons own arbitrary conceptions, otherwise it takes the much more difficult task of impressing a foreign concept without any obvious framework into a mind which has become accustomed to thinking in frameworks.  It's much easier to convince people that something is normal if it's framed as within a normal category, or like another normal thing. Likewise it's almost impossible to teach most people whole new concepts, especially after about age 22.  It seems like the real problem is that the categories we live with have degraded into a problematic obsolescence. How can we repurpose the concepts of gender and validity to get the fuck out of the way, or ditch them entirely?

This seems as good a place as it's gonna get to understand. I'm a male who has grown up in a very lgbt friendly country, i've had straight, bi, and gay friends, i've worked with trans people, and worked for drag queens. I've never minded any of them, it made me quite happy that they could be who they wanted to be without any judgement. However, what bothers me greatly is people wanting to be spoken to with they/them pronouns. I don't mind what anyone does with their life but that stands as long as it doesn't affect me. You wanted to be racist, be my guest, just don't go blaming immigrants for stealing your jobs when i'm around. You support extremely leftists groups? Fine with me, just don't go and try to shame me into also having to feel like i need to support your cause. I feel the same way with people who want to be spoken to with they/them pronouns. If you have your social groups where people are comfortable in speaking to you like that. Great! Glad that makes you happy, but why do i need to conform to that as well? Why is it bad for me to speak to a person with either he or she, when my first instinct would be for either one. There shouldn't be that much weight to it in my opinion. You already feel disconnected from either pronoun so why is it that me saying he or she than is incorrect?   Then what i have come up with in my own hours under the shower trying to understand is the following. There are certain stereotypes associated with being a he or she, and for someone to then be spoken to as he/she whilst feeling a disassociation with that pronoun can be triggering, as it doesn't confine with what they have made their own box (in this case being they/them boxes). So if that would be the case, would it then not be easier for a society as a whole to keep he and she and have (arguably) the minority redefine what it means to them personally to be he or she?  I.E. I might call a person who would identify as they/them, he. Instead of that person telling me that he wants to be called they, that person has 'reprogrammed' himself to take that 'he' as a fluid. A case of: Give words less power, instead of more words more power.  Closing statement. I kind of relate to this. I totally support everyone including non-binary people no matter how they identify or how extreme their gender expression may seem to me. But at the same time I can't help feeling weird when exposed to an abstract vague depiction of gender. I guess it makes me kind of dysphoric because even though I'm trans I'm extremely binary I feel my male identity  very strongly but I can't  explain why. If you strip away society's ideas of gender and say that nothing is gendered then how do I validate and express myself. For example I started testosterone and enjoy growing a beard because it makes me feel like a 'real man' but I know damn well that you can be a man with out a bread and  women or non-binary people who choose to rock a beard have every right to do so and I support that very much. So what do I have that's solely male that I can embrace as part of my identity. As you can see  it's not a problem with them it's a problem with me I can't imagine being anything other than a man or a woman. like when I try to imagine that blind people don't see black darkness because they don't see all and what that would be like. or if I try to imagine what it would be like to not exist like if that's what death is. It's a strong sense of existential dread. If that's how some cis people feel when discussing any trans issues then I guess I understand why they would lash out. On the topic of trans trending, I would never judge someone or treat them differently because of it but there are times when I see someone expressing what appears to be a very superficial idea of gender like it's a fashion statement some sort of fun game, saying they don't need dysphoria to be trans and stuff. it just feels a little  disrespectful because it's very serious to a lot of people and not some light-hearted choice.  But still no matter these internal feelings that arise and I can't really control I'm not judging anyone based on how they feel about gender or how they choose to express that gender. Sometimes the liberal left gets a little overbearing I wish you could express honest feelings like this stating that it's just a fact about how I feel and it's not meant as an attack without it always being twisted to be something insulting. I respect these people but I admit that the concept baffles me and the two are not mutually exclusive. the point is  feeling this way is not an excuse to be an asshole.

The argument about gay people not having to logically explain why they are gay really hit close to home. I am Polish, living in Poland, an extremely homophobic country. The whole politics right now is built around the majority party using 'the gay problem' to scare Poles into voting for them. As homosexuals are being shown as the greatest evil (literally, it's disgusting and shocking what the majority party is saying about them), the small portion of the Left that is, well... left  (lol)in Poland (none of them in the parliament...) is beating their brains out trying to find logical, rational, scientific arguments for why being gay is both natural and non-theatening. That's why I was a little taken aback when the character said that gay people don't have to explain why they are that way, they simply are. Now, I do realise gay people in the USA still experience homophobia in various shape and form, but I can see how being gay is more generally accepted there (even the right has their own gay representatives like the infamous Milo) and not oficially said to be a threat to the safety of the country.  I know, it's become a rant about polish politics lol...... Oh GAWD, what am I? I'm so confused.... nought.  My gender is NOT defined by my genitals, it is defined by those meta-things we call feelings and thoughts.  I first experienced gender dysphoria at the age of nine; it was 1969 and there was nowhere for me to turn to. a few years later Renae Richards was being talked about on TV as one who transitioned from male to female and I literally thought that there is still hope for me. Here I am half a fucking century later and question the cisnormative treatment that is gender-confirming surgery which focuses primarily on cosmetic surgery of one's genitals and potentially destroying one's ability at sexual pleasure, but, and this is a big but, not a booty butt, but a but-but, lol, it does nothing for helping one fit into society. When people are walking down the street and see another person, they do not decide on the sex of that person by looking at the genitals or sniffing each other's butts. Sexuality is determined by how your facial features have developed due to the dominant hormones in your body. I see so many trans people who have transitioned and I can clock them because the transition took place late in life and birth hormones(mostly testosterone) has left its mark with a more pronounced brow, a stronger chin etc etc. For women transitioning into men, I do not believe it is as powerful as the testosterone replacement therapy will change their features and their voice. Not so for M2F transfolk whose only answer is facial feminization surgery. which is not covered in Canada. But mutilating my genitalia is. Let's be real here, gender confirmation surgery is cosmetic surgery of the genitalia and if it works for you, all the power to you, but it doesn't work for me. I do not define myself by my genitalia, I define myself by those amorphous nonphysical attributes called thoughts and feelings.    My genitals are my business. My gender reflects how I wish to interact with the rest of society. In some ways, I see myself as hermaphroditic, not in the true sense of the word, but in the sense that my gender is of one sex while my genitalia is of another.   EVERYTHING IS A SPECTRUM. 'What makes nonbinary people nonbinary?'  Well for me, it's feeling like gender roles/restrictions/expectations have absolutely NO personal relevance to who I know myself to be / what I want to do. I don't notice and I don't care about noticing. But then again I'm probably more at the 'agender' end of the spectrum. I am a 'genders? no thanks' person.  Meanwhile, I have friends who enjoy & care passionately about being feminine AND being masculine, at their own pace, and identify as genderfluid. They are a 'genders? yes thank you' person. (Note: 'nonbinary' is an umbrella term that includes genderfluid, bigender, polygender, and similar identities)  The funny part is, we can both end up with similar appearances when it comes to gender performance, since we've both decided we're gonna do whatever the hell we want, when we want. We just have different reasons for doing so.  I'm not more valid for saying 'gender roles are made up' and they're not more valid for saying 'I am both feminine and masculine'. Neither of us are inherently more woke or valid than people who say 'I am a woman', 'I am a man', 'I am a gender-nonconforming woman', or 'I am a gender-nonconforming man'. Yes, all gender roles are made up. Yes, your femininity/masculinity is still real. It's not a contest. We are who we are, we don't have to prove anything to anyone. We're all stuck on this bitch of an earth and the least y'all could do is not make another person's day worse, if you can help it. That's it. It ain't rocket science.  In other words, I agree with the conclusion of this video.

Amazing video - I have to admit I've had trouble wrapping my head around the arguments you posed.  Perhaps because I'm a cis-het male who's never wrestled with my gender identity - I've been fortunate enough to never have to do the deep-dive into what is gender you have outlined throughout your videos.  The 'conventional definition' has been good enough for me to couch my sense of gender identity. As a scientist, I find the hardest part of answering a question is in defining the question - especially a concept that is a human construct based on a thought or sensation (like what is music, what is blue or what is salty).  Concepts need a hard definition to resolve debate (e.g. when is noon, or which direction is North) and so far Webster's dictionary and Medicine are still struggling to generate a solid consensus, especially in light of the evolving discussions on gender and genderqueer legislation.  In the meantime, I guess we have the definition of gender you pose in the video being a superposition of physical, psychological, and social qualities - and we base the metric by having many examples we can point to as 'typical' and 'demonstrative'.  But that can also affirm the idea that gender can be a bimodal distribution, and a fraction of us simply do not fit within 2 standard deviations into one of the two 'classical' gender roles.  I wish it was easy to define, it might save a lot of people grief in their search for validation in their sense of identity.  Finally, I think it is also interesting you note that the value in identifying one's gender is to decide how to properly interact with them.  Do I say 'sir' or 'madam', or how I look at them or talk to them in a meaningful and socially appropriate way?  Or do I really need to identify one's gender at all to recognize that this person still at least has rights under the law and feeling that can be hurt?  Is it even practical to have gender (or race) in a 'woke' society?  Definitely an interesting thought.  Thanks again for your video - it continues to challenge me (in a good way).  And sorry for the attempted dissertation in your comments section, I hope it makes a bit of sense in it's brevity.

As a side note anecdote, I'm chronically depressed and have attention deficit disorder, and I never had to take a brain scan for this, however I did take a battery of psychometric tests and spent a time under 2 different psychiatrist (concomitantly) and a psychologist until they arrived on a consensus. It's indirect evidence, and sometimes this is close enough to justify the diagnosis, especially when the doctors keep the patient under observation after prescribing medicines to see if the medicines are functioning properly due to the correct diagnosis (this is vital on depression, for example, as the wrong medicine can increase suicidal ideation). Personally, I never felt sad, and would never guess I'm depressed before the event that made me look for medical help (panic syndrome after a turbulent relationship), as I believed that depression was utter sadness... I always looked at the world with complete apathy and disconnectedness, not sadness. I guess this is why I have always been interested in radical politics, because they are about belonging and not being. I think this is a good video, but I think there's something to be said for the part about mental disorders and brain scans. Because I think it invalidates a lot of people who have been diagnosed with other mental illnesses.  Does everyone get a brain scan to diagnose a mental illness they might have?  No. I've been diagnosed without a brain scan.  Does that mean there's no physical basis for these diagnoses?  Not really because brain scans of other people who were diagnosed with this disorder have shown differences in brain structure between people with a diagnosis and people without one.  But if I didn't have a brain scan, how do I know whether or not I'm one of these people?  I guess for sure, I don't know. And that part of the video kind of has a point, because no one ever scanned my brain. But a mental health professional who is familiar with the type of people who have this diagnosis and has been trained in diagnosing people based on a set of traits that we typically share, did give me a diagnosis and that's how a lot of mental health diagnoses go down. I don't think it's fair to say that 'if you don't scan someone's brain, then there's no proof of a disorder.' It's kind of like saying 'Even if you clearly have all the physical symptoms of an illness, we really just can't prove anything until the test results come back.'

How people see you, treat you, or interact with you can make you feel like you are in the wrong place. For some other people, it's behavioral. Your actions that you do based on either societal upbringing or physicality. Need to adjust your pants or manspread cause your dick is in the wrong place? That's a masculine presenting behavior. I've always identified as a cis lesbian, but lately I've been wondering if I'm really a cis woman. I have a few masculine features that I shouldn't be comfortable with, and yet I am. I often have short dark hairs growing out of my chin, and it doesn't faze me in the slightest. I don't like shaving my legs or armpits, not as a feminist way of showing that shaving is unnecessary, but because I'm more comfortable as a hairy beast. Sometimes I wish my voice was deeper, not because I want to sound more masculine, but I think if I had a deeper voice, people would take me seriously. I like wearing men's clothes, and I like dudebro action movies. And despite all that, I don't feel any dysphoria at all. I'm not even a little bit uncomfortable when I look at my chest, hips, and whatnot, same as I am perfectly fine with having a hairy chin. I've never had a problem with using she/her pronouns, but if I'm comfortable being this masculine, am I really a woman? When I think of it, I think I'd be fine using any pronouns, really. I like feminine things, and I like being vaguely feminine. I like masculine things, and I like being vaguely masculine. I don't ever experience any discomfort in my masculine features or my feminine features, but it feels like I should be. I like calling myself a cis girl, but I'm not sure I am? I personally don't believe that transtrenders exist in the first place. I find it highly hypocritical to be offended at TERFS for being assholes and then insulting other trans people because their experience of being trans doesn't match your very shallow definition of it. Are there some people who thought they were trans and ended up backpedaling after a month or so? Of course. Why? Gender identity is confusing and there is nothing wrong with experimenting with different labels. That's why there is such a proliferation of gender identities in Tumblr. It's people--typically younger people--who are experimenting. Their experimentation isn't hurting anyone so I don't see the big deal. You also have to take into account that gender is a social construct and is inextricably tied to the cultures that created it in the first place. This is why what is and isn't female is so inconsistent across cultures and time. It turns out that different people from different areas have differing ideas jus like how different people from the same area have differing ideas. Is there a psychological aspect to gender? Well, of course! Our very sense of self is tied to our brain and our psychology. Social contructs do have power though as Contrapoints pointed out in her NonBinary identity video. Money like gender has power over society and both can force people into tiny little boxes in which the minorities have little freedom. This is why I believe we--as a society--needs to be more accepting to those who are different from us. Although we may have differences in race, finances, politics, gender identity, and sexual orientation; we are still human beings living in a very difficult world. Life is hard enough without us goal keeping what is and isn't valid or which people even get to exist in the first place. We're all human, and I think we can find some solidarity in that! Thanks for taking the time to read this essay!

This is a very well thought out video. I'm very impressed with the production quality and the philosophical exploration of ideas. I also appreciate that your bias was stated although a little subtly. You can't have a true debate without getting a bit of emotional baggage out of the way. I'd have to say that I'm somewhere in between being strict and being just not caring about what people do. Although I'd like a bigger exploration into how gender expression and sexuality differ and if gender expression really is different to gender identity. I say this because I had my own gender crisis over being a lesbian. I feel like a lot of people aren't just the peak of femininity or a flannel wearing tomboy. We're somewhere in between. My crisis was about not really identifying with the dominating butch/androgyne or the pillow princess lip stick (not that being one is a bad thing). The truth is that you can be a submissive butch. You can be an effeminate dominatrix. You can be neither. You can be both. Its just a style. A personality type. Not who you are as a person. Lesbians can like dildos. There! I said it! I will also say that I don't think its necessarily a bad thing to be classified as a mental disorder. All it implies is that you simply cannot function with the way you are at that moment. It is diagnosed in a way as anxiety or depression or body dysmorphia is diagnosed. Of course it has to do with your feelings. It has everything to do with your feelings! That doesn't mean your identity isn't any less valid. If anything, it means you're more valid. What I identify as a 'transtrender' (there needs to be a better word) is someone who isn't necessarily UNcomfortable with they're assigned sex and identity, but is questioning based on things like they're breasts, sexuality, abuse, or expression. I wouldn't say they're completely sane in the head, but it would be difficult to say they would benefit from transitioning. However, they do it anyway to feel accepted and secure. No one should be forced to transition in order to feel accepted. Its okay to be questioning. Its also okay to say you think you're questioning. What I would recommend is to experiment with social transitioning. Watch testimonies from both happy trans people and detransitioners. Learn the effects of procedures. Learn what can go wrong. Do you envision yourself growing old in your identity? Do you feel emotional pain when being identified as your birth identity/sex? Do have any underlying anxiety, depression, or self esteem issues that could be causing you to reject your identity? Is it from the wanting of a fresh start/acceptance or is it of your own want/discomfort with your body? Is it your expression that is bothering you? These are all very deep and exploratory questions that I have had to ask myself over and over again. Sometimes I just had to experience reality and get out of my thoughts. See what I feel in that moment instead of thinking what I should feel or what I could feel. I identify as a cis lesbian btw.

I'm a left leaning centrist. I don't literally pick the halfway point between the left and right views on an issue. Instead, I listen to both sides and figure out which one I agree with more. For 80% of issues, I'm on the left (especially human rights issues.)  For example, abortion: I don't think that only half of all abortions should be allowed. Instead I'm pretty firmly pro-choice.   Another example: I think all speech needs to be free, outside of the 'fire' in a crowded theatre.   Another example: I think all LGBT+ people deserve the right to be married, to not lose their jobs or house/apartment/etc for being LGBT+, and that every right a cis hetero person has, an LGBT+ person deserves the exact same. I don't believe that we should only let lesbians get married but not gay men or that gay women aren't valid but gay men are. (Also, gonna mention I'm the B in LGBT+, don't know that's relevant or not, but I thought I'd mention it lol)  Idk if contra was just joking there, I mean yes, she was obviously joking with the 2 & 1/2 gender thing. But, is the joke: 'haha, a half gender is absurd,' or 'Dave Ruben is an idiot who cant pick a side, Haha'   Or, it: 'Centrists are idiots who can't pick sides Haha.'  Here's the thing, I don't believe in dogmatically adhering to one side of the partisan aisle on every political issue. I value thinking about each individual issue and coming to my own conclusions; it just so happens that for me, the majority of those conclusions happen to fall on the left. This is why I call myself a left leaning centrist.  I've just noticed a lot of hostility lately towards people who call themselves centrists by channels on left-tube. With a false interpretation to what centrists stand for. Not just this video, but similar jokes in an hbomberguy video, a philosophy tube video  and others I'm forgetting right now (I think, maybe folding ideas or a Lindsay Ellis video, but don't quote me on that.)  I mean, it's really making me wonder, do you guys honestly think that the centrist stance is to find the exact middle of an argument from the left and right, then decide on a mutated 'compromise' on the issues? That we think that 50% of all abortions should be legal? Or the LGBT+ community should only get 50% of the rights heteros get. That's pretty much the jist of the recurring centrist jokes I've been hearing lately.  There's a comment on this video with 308 likes currently that is just this: 'As for how many genders there are, y'know, I'm gonna take the centrist route and say 2 1/2.'   It's just the joke I'm referring to, quoted directly from this video. Which reinforcing that many people really found it hilarious and it seems like it's just laughing at a strawman of what a centrist actually is.   So, I'm asking everyone here... As a fan of Contrapoints, hbomberguy, and a lot of other left-tube channels, but also someone who watches channels on the right and a fan of some of them, too...  Do you really think of centrists this way? Is centrist like a dirty word to you? Do you think someone who calls themselves a centrist as nothing more than a stupid person?  To me, never listening to other opinions and strictly adhering to a dogma of only the right or the left is stupid. Challenging your own opinions by listening to the other side is something I find extremely valuable.  The following quote is how I pretty much view my own conclusions I come to on political discourse. Even though this quote is attributed to Aristotle, there is an argument over whether or not it's a real quote, however, I still think it sums up how a centrist, or at least this one, views politics.  'It is the mark of an educated mind to be able to entertain a thought without accepting it.'

I could see and understand most of the arguments made from both sides.   I think there could be a difference in definitions between different people, but I believe gnc people aren't inherently trans. That gnc just don't conform to gender roles/binary rules. While I consider non-binary as an innate thing. Like a binary trans person. Something you are born with due to misalignment with the brain. Gnc being a choice.  gnc does not = non-binary But most non-binary people dress androgynous or non conforming.  Gnc people may use non-binary pronouns, but gnc people choose to present and go about themselves and their identities differently than how they were assigned at birth. Highlighted word here is CHOOSE. Because they p r e f e r not to be put into restricting boxes society has of men and women. Which could be a different definition to someone else. Maybe gnc is the same as non-binary to someone else, but I think they're set apart by definitions of gnc=choose to present how they do and non-binary=have dysphoria and have to present/transition to lessen their dysphoria. Transgender people do not choose to be the way they are, and I think that distinction is important.   Though with saying that I guess the rebuttal would be(and what was on the video), 'how is a gnc person different and why aren't their feelings as valid as 'real' trans people.' And what I would say to that is that there are VAST differences and experiences between gnc and trans people. Especially binary trans people. I think there needs to be a distinction between trans people because a bunch of people are being thrown under the label that is too broad.  What most people try to distinguish between transgenderism and transsexualism. If a male presenting amab person(who identifies as trans) is given a platform to speak or talk on trans issues, I don't think it represents the majority of the trans community and is unfair to group them in with someone like a trans woman who has undergone all the surgeries and hormone treatment. Not being an ample voice for trans people, basically. Because their experience is vastly different from the other, so they are hardly comparable and therefore should not be out under the same label.  And if I make ANY kind of argument mentioning the public eye people will bring up how that's societies problem because they don't understand. And as said in the video, conformity to try 'winning acceptance.'  I don't believe it's conformity to 'try to win acceptance' but the majority experience of trans people to not be ignored or covered up by those who have much different experiences. The majority of trans people I have met and encountered want and actively try(who are able to) present as their identified gender. Eventually medically transitioning for themselves to lessen their dysphoria(unless for some legit reason unable to). I think the distinction between people having/needing a medical intervention for their gender dysphoria vs people who just outwardly present differently should be recognized. But then again, the video mentioned how that apparently leaves out people who are questioning or whatever. But those who are questioning are just- questioning? They can't identify themselves as trans or cis till their figure it out.   I am not trying to invalidate other non-binary people or gnc, just trying to say it should be considered a different thing because of vast experience differences.  Non-binary is at an overlapping grey area between trans and simply non-binary as its own thing. Because of it not always being a medical thing.   Gnc by it's own is not a medical thing.  And it's important to not demedicalize transgenderism/transsexualism(however you want to define it as) because to most(can I say all? I think I can say all) transgender people it is important and vital to transition(excluding those who want to, but can't transition due to medical reasons, unsupportive family, financial issues, etc).  Transgenderism and transitioning isn't to break the boxes society has, while non-binary and mostly gnc that's what it is. Their identity breaks boxes whether they intend to or not.  While binary trans people are wanting to/transitioning into the other binary gender. Aka into the binary boxes. Not meaning they are hyper masculine if they are a trans guy or hyper feminine if a trans woman. Just that they are male or female. Which is within societies boxes. We aren't trying to lick cis boots or conform to be accepted. We are 'conforming' to be the gender we are.  Non-binary and gnc should not be considered the same thing as binary trans people who plan/want to medically transition. Non-binary is kinda tricky as it's half and half, but I think it is still important to have enough distinction to have them within their own and not take on the trans label-? So I guess I am just sounding like a massive exclusionist. Am a massive exclusionist I guess. Which I guess I haven't realized till now.   Feel free to bring up any points/arguments I have or that may have been in the video that I missed/forgot about that would have been a good rebuttal to anything I said. I'm curious and open as to how others think and consider these ideas. I am willing to listen and/or talk to anyone with similar or simple text different opinions/thoughts as long as you're respectful.

I think the distinction between transgender and transsexual is important, that way people that have dysphoria due to their biology can have a label to distinguish themselves from people that have dysphoria or discomfort with the societal roles expected of them. A person that wants to transition to the opposite biological schema but not adopt the associated gender performance is distinct from someone that wants to keep their anatomy the way it is but adopt a disparate social role. Transgender could then refer to mere gender transition whereas transsexual could refer to mere biological transition. Both could occur in the same person but both are not required to be 'trans.'

*Contra makes a great point here.* The *Socratic Dialogue* is the best way to engage in conversation, especially concerning politics and opinion. Because *a debate is a war, and a conversation is an Alliance!* You see,  I've been debating for years through middle school, high school, college and well... As a lawyer, that's pretty much what I do for a living. And something that I've realized, is that the Socratic Dialogue is the probably the best way to both access people's feelings as well as to (most importantly) convert them to your way of thinking. You can never convince, say, a Right winger (or anyone else for that matter) through debate. Because what I've learned is that debate always means *war* 99% of the time. While a wholesome heart-to-heart conversation is *an alliance* . And I feel that the Socratic method of conversation is by far the best way to get your feelings across, while also Sympathizing with others' ideas. Yes, Right wing ideas might be horrible and deplorable, but you have to get through their layers of personality and opinion to find out why they adopted such ideas. You then discover that some traumatic experience in their childhood or early development period is what made them behave that way or posess that deplorable opinion, and at that point, since you are already layers deep into their mind, you'll be able to convince and deradicalise them much more easily!

Why do people get angry when men speak on behalf of women's issues? Why do people get angry when white people speak on behalf of black issues? Probably for the same reason that Blaire White gets upset when non-binary people speak on behalf of trans issues.  For a minute, let's put aside the whole issue of trying to determine which people are 'valid' or not. After all, when a woman gets upset that a man is speaking on behalf of women's issues, she is not claiming that the man is 'invalid', merely that he is ill fit to speak on women's issues. Likewise, when a black person gets upset that a white person is speaking on behalf of black issues, they are claiming that this white person is 'invalid'. Now, you may disagree and think it is fully acceptable for men to speak on women's issues or white people to speak on black issues. Or you might not. But either way, the argument has nothing to do with who is 'valid' and who is not. It has to do with people's experiences and problems related to a specific subgroup in the community.   Trans people like Blaire White have very specific issues that they face and causes that they may fight for which are very different from the issues which Non-Binary people are working to solve. And Blaire, as far as I can tell, is arguing that mixing the two forms of activism together results in them causing problems for the other side, stepping on each other's toes or one group taking precedence over the other, etc. After all, we can't actively fight for every single worthy cause all at the same time, that's simply impossible. There's not enough time nor enough public interest to solve all the world's problems at once. This means some causes will naturally take priority over others. And if Non-binary people are being taken more seriously than trans people then, at least by Blaire's logic, trans issues are ignored in favor of Non-Binary problems.    Why do so many feminists reject/belittle men's issues so much? Because they believe men's issues distract from the issues faced by women or that solving men's issues will negatively impact/make worse the issues faced by women.   If you support the way feminists demean and belittle men's rights activists, then as far as I'm concerned, you have no room to talk when it comes to Blaire's views on the trans movement. But if you support both feminists and men's rights activists (or would like to see both groups come together in a egalitarian movement), then disagreeing with Blaire's stance, to me, is fair and consistent. If people could just be consistent with what they believe, I really don't care where you ultimately fall on the issue. I just wish people could stop being hypocrites.

What I walk away with from the discussion at the end is that we can have a theory for an individual trans person's identity, but we can never have a unified theory, because people come into trans gender identities for wildly different reasons. Some people transition to fit into a gender role, some to break it. Some have 'phantom limb' sensations of a differently sexed body, some genuinely believe they are autogynephiles. Some have had a trans gender identity since before they knew what genitals were, some believe they repressed their true identity for most of their life, and some genuinely believe they changed their gender identity. No theory can unify all of these people. Tiffany Tumbles is actually right about this part: aside from sharing a disprivileged gender identity, she really isn't anything like Baltimore. This doesn't mean we should stop examining the causes and meanings of trans gender identity scientifically and philosophically, a position I despise. But we should all recognize that trans gender identity does not have a single unifying cause or explanation, and we need to in order to truly empathize with each other and fight for our rights. To do that, we need to start by recognizing that if one person is misrepresenting how another trans person feels, it isn't necessarily because they are a 'trender' or 'truscum' but because they feel like their own story is being trampled on or misrepresented. For example, I often find myself frustrated with gender performativity theorists because my personality and hobbies are quite androgynous but I consider myself a woman, not at all non-binary, because I identify fully with the female body. But I need to resist the temptation to talk over them and tell them that they are confused about why they are trans, and instead explain that gender roles and performance have nothing to do with my own trans gender identity, while acknowledging at least the possibility that this theory might most accurately explain why they have a trans identity.

Gender disphoria vs cultural transgender is pretty much like physiological depression vs self-perceived depression. One is a medical issue, the other isn't, but goddammit can we respect BOTH, please? That way if you're trans and have GD then you can get the medical treatment you need - including SRS - and if you're trans and don't have GD you can identify yourself the way you're comfortable with, period, without fucking laypeople trying to use people who don't have GD to deny treatment for people who DO have GD.  And yes, I do mean that people who don't have physiological symptoms of depression don't need meds, but they do need therapy and have to be respected, instead of being used to deny treatment to people who truly do need antidepressants to survive.  Acknowledging different issues that look the same as different is more intelligent than trying to shove everyone in the same basket. Reminds me of 10-20 years ago (and probably earlier) where the big topic was finding genetic validity of gayness. The idea that anyone would give a fuck about that these days is honestly jarring, it's not even 'born this way' anymore it's just 'yeah that's a thing.' I think this whole search for scientific validity is just a stepping stone in society's attempt to understand something new, compulsively categorizing what it is and isn't until it just blends in with the clutter and its existence is taken for granted. People like Baltimore are scary in this tenuous era of trans acceptance, but they're not going to just pop out of existence until it becomes more convenient. It's very easy to look at a glitter-beared They and think 'can't they just tone it down?' but it's much harder to look at yourself and your own idiosyncrasies, however milder they probably are, and confront how unfair and intolerable it'd be if someone demanded YOU 'just tone it down.' There's a reason Baltimore walks around with a glitter beard and you don't.Once you truly accept yourself and stop allowing others to determine the worth, validity and limits of your identity, once you stop living in that cage and feel that freedom, you can finally look at others and understand that they shouldn't be caged either. You can grant YOURSELF that freedom, you don't need to wait for society to give it to you. Yes, some people might look at Baltimore and then judge Tiffany by what they saw, but it's ultimately Tiffany's choice whether to accept that burden, as if Baltimore is an extension of herself that she has any control over. But it goes both ways, too. As much as the Tiffanies of the world can be abrasive and mean, at the end of the day they're trying to defend their access to medical treatment that they believe is vital to their quality of life, just like the Baltimores of the world are defending the freedom of self-expression that they believe is vital to theirs. Neither can come at the expense of the other, but whenever in-fighting occurs it's as if there can be only one. Just feel it's worth a mention, because I really do see the Baltimores of the world often taking their own lack of dependence on medicine for granted in their attitudes towards trans medicalism, so it's no wonder that the latter group sometimes feels threatened. But that's the beauty of no longer living with the chains of prejudice, you can be individuals and pursue what you personally need to feel whole without worrying about jostling or being jostled by the next person on the chain. Anyway, that's my unstructured rant, thanks for the thought-food, now I must rest.

I don't know if anyone brought this up yet, but the American Psychiatric Association, which publishes the DSM-5 (the current diagnostic system for psychiatric disorders, making this pretty representative of the 'medical community') doesn't really support Tiffany's perspective. The classification of gender dysphoria was created in 2013 to replace gender identity disorder, specifically to focus on 'dysphoria as the clinical problem, not [transgender] identity per se.' The manual makes it pretty clear that it is not a diagnosis for anyone with 'an incongruence between one's experienced or expressed gender and one's assigned gender,' but only for those for whom it results in 'clinically significant distress or impairment in social, school, or other important areas of functioning.'

This is one of the best videos I've seen on the philosophical questions underlying gender and identity. I can honestly say, it's really illuminating for a straight white guy like myself and I really appreciate what you do, Natalie.  The way I see it is... Gender is a social construct. Meaning, there's nothing real about it on a material level. Gender is whatever we want it to be, whatever we say it is as a society. However, our *beliefs* in gender (and gender roles) have material consequences. The longstanding oppression of women by patriarchal norms, as an example. I can't blame the women who feel hurt by the presence of people who seem to freely 'play' with gender as if oppression can just be turned on or off at a whim. I can see how some might see it as frivolous and dismissive. However, I don't think any of this needs to invalidate anyone's identity. Isn't identity itself a social construct? Yet, identities have material consequences as well. It seems to me that the feminist project has always been to expose gender for the construct it is. The inevitable goal might be total abolition of gender as a concept. Perhaps a future world would be one in which everyone is radically individualistic and free from any sort of gender signifiers or constraints. But as long as patriarchy exists, this can never be achieved. As long as patriarchy exists, so do the material consequences of the roles it demands from its subjects and all the hurt that goes along with that.  I personally think that if we want to take liberation seriously and work to build a world where everyone is radically free, we need to accept everyone's identities as valid. Yes, even if you want to identify as a cat. It sounds silly, yes, but people who experiment this deeply with their identity are likely still searching for themselves and constructing a more permanent identity or role in society. Let people experiment. Let people find themselves. I think validating radical modes of living and identities can be a revolutionary and liberating practice. And perhaps that includes validating the hurt some people feel from class oppression of any kind. I think we all struggle, and I think we all assume that others struggle less than we do.  I dunno, I'm thinking out loud here. This is a difficult topic, but I find it powerful and interesting to think about and I hope the left can start to become less divided by thinking these things through and talking about them with each other.

Great video Contra. My only concern is that by basing our ontology purely on internal identity, we lose what categories actually mean. What if there's another option? What if we say that gender as a category doesn't have to be prescriptive? What if gender is just a descriptive category of the traits that maps onto the bimodal distribution of biological sex, and we can just not enforce gender roles? I feel like that's an easier solution. Because if you base what someone 'is' purely off of their internal sense of identity, then what identities does that apply to? Is it just gender, or can we do race as well? If we don't have to meet any standards or traits that we associate with certain categories so that we are perceived as that category, is Rachel Dolezal actually black then? Can anyone say they're anything and we have to accept it? And is it wrong if we do not perceive people how they perceive themselves? Like if someone does not perceive a trans woman as a woman, or Rachel Dolezal as black, is that transphobic? What does it even mean to 'be' something? Is it just a feeling? And does that feeling have to be based in something objective about yourself? Can you 'feel' like anything? With trans identity, we seem to all agree that people can 'feel' like other genders- can people 'feel' like other races? Other species? I'm not trying to be silly here, it's a real question. Where do we draw the line?    I'm not even entirely sure what identity means anymore. We seem to have taken the idea of  'third person perception based on observable traits' and then formed a mental category based on that, turn that mental category into a word, and we then take that word divorce it from what it originally meant, and then try to apply it to 'first-person identity based in experience.' And there's something about that that I think we get wrong. I think trans identity is valid, and I want to accept everyone's identity as what they say it is, but I just... I think there is a middle ground that you missed. If there is a binary male and female then there would be an outgroup, which would be non binary. For every box or group, there is inherently an an out group or outside of the box. There is also a difference between gender expression and dysphoria. Gender expression can be on a spectrum, and we should be respectful of people's gender expression. If someone goes by they/ them or whatever they feel most comfortable with, I think it is only respectful to accommodate. My wife (who is trans) has a bit more of a conservative view than I do, but would still be respectful of someone, she has a view that gender itself is a combination of biological characteristics and social ones. Primarily secondary sexual characteristics, since those are what is socially looked at to identify someone's gender. Since she does struggle with gender dysphoria, she doesn't quite get people who don't who are trans. On the other hand, I think you can very easily not fit into either box, which is where non binary comes from, dysphoric non binary people makes sense. For people who don't have dysphoria, but don't want to be constrained by societies narrow definition of what is and isn't a specific gender imo could have any range of gender expression and go by whatever they want in the process. They seem to be deconstructing the societal expectations of each gender and just expressing themselves however they like. I wouldn't exactly call those people trans though (at least in the context of transitioning, but they would definitely be trans in the sense of across gender), I feel that something like genderqueer or  not othering it at all would work. I think in the future the societal constructs of gender will be deconstructed to the point where all gender expressions will be seen as just that, a gender expression, but when that time comes, people who need to medically transition their bodies, due to dysphoria will still exist. I don't think 'transtrenders' are being trending, I think they are changing societies perceptions (very very slowly). There can both be medically necessary trans individuals who need to physically transition and people who want to embrace the gender expression that makes them the most comfortable. I almost feel there should be 2 different categories for it so that they don't get confused by the mainstream. Because while technically both would be trans, they are 2 completely different experiences and mean 2 different things. I don't know maybe we could use genderqueer for people who don't have dysphoria and trans for people who do. Because queer is like atypical, which could describe the atypical gender expression, while trans would describe the transition across genders. Just an idea, so that the 2 very different things don't get combined.

Here's my take on it (nobody asked, but I'd like to discuss!): Everyone is right and wrong at the same time. I have two problems with the trans-trender phenomenon, and neither are about how good or bad individuals are, or how they should or should not present. It is about the phenomenon of trends themselves, and how they may affect people. 1: If it's trendy to be trans, lots of people are going to receive the wrong treatment. Bottom surgery on a non-trans person is... Well; functionally irreversible. And puberty-blockers carry their own developmental issues; once your skeleton is set, it's not going to grow according to a renewed puberty, to name one thing. 2: If gender is (ultimately) a choice, then health insurance companies have no reason to fund transgender treatment like hormones and surgery. That... Is an outcome that is inevitable if all of gender is viewed as non-biological. And I'll be honest; that prospect scares me.   Before I continue, here's three summaries of how I view gender: Gender role: This is performative.  Gender category: Like all categories, a social construct. Gendered behaviour: Behaviour informed by sex-typical neurobiology. This is the stuff we naturally do; gender here is emergent from biology. These three things are all real, and all different.   Now; individuals are different. Some people are more masculine, some people are more feminine, and these differences can depend on topic.  This is where I get to non-binary: I don't think it's a useful category, because with a binary system that is on a spectrum, _everyone_ is non-binary. Everyone sits somewhere else on that spectrum. Of course, the same can be said for pan- and bisexuality. So I do: Everyone is, to a larger or greater degree, pansexual. The strength of your preferences on that spectrum (in part) determines how people categorize themselves. I believe sexual preference disgust is purely performative. I also believe that most people strongly prefer people of one sex over the other, but that is, again, a matter of where you sit on a spectrum. Now comes identity: It is fine if you _identify_ as non-binary. But it is an identity. It is not a gender, but a club that you have categorized yourself as belonging to. In fact, I think it's perfectly valid to create as many categories as you like. I don't think it's _useful,_ but it is perfectly valid. So yeah, I don't think identifying as a gender (in itself) is any more (or less) valid than identifying as a dragon. Of course: Gendered behaviour is a thing, whereas Dragonned behaviour is not (though Dragon role does exist; you can be a performative Dragon). That's where the difference lies between the two.   Most people I know do not identify with their gender. Their gender is just traits. Some of it is indeed performative because cultural normativity. Some of it is not. Most people _just do not care._ If they did care, and did assign gendered categories to all of their personality aspects, and they did think of those as parts of their identity, then they would all have to conclude that... They're non-binary. Which is the primary reason I believe that that category is not useful outside of a subcultural identity.   (Also: Gender dysphoria =/ trans. I've had gender dysphoria. It passed because I learnt to deal with the root causes. Not trans. I'm just insane in other ways, and a culmination of contexts caused me to have severely dysphoric symptoms regarding gender and sex. I also believe that not all trans people are dysphoric. If you're have a male-typical brain and are perfectly okay with having a female body, then there's a good chance you won't suffer (much) dysphoria. So if you are naturally inclined towards more male-typical behaviour than female-typical behaviour, then I will categorize your gender as 'man.' Regardless of your sex. If you disagree with my categorization, then that's perfectly fine, but the way we categorize the world is up to ourselves, and nobody can tell you that your categorization system is invalid.)

Technically, we don't conduct brain scans on people we ultimately diagnose with conditions such as depression, anxiety, ADHD, schizophrenia, even autism spectrum disorder. All these conditions, like gender dysphoria, can be detected on brain scans since they result in atypical brain patterns. Gender dysphoria is a result of abnormal natal hormone exposure that forms a grey/white matter ratio that reflects the opposite sex rather than the person's assigned sex.  While I see the point of the argument, the reason why we don't do brain scans on patients with gender dysphoria is due to cost and such. Since we rely on psychotherapy to diagnose mental illnesses, the medical community has decided to trust the DSM 5 criteria to diagnose dysphoria rather than needing a costly brain scan with a long wait time in order to confirm it. There is a biological basis to gender dysphoria and it could be detected if someone were to run the tests for it. I have yet to see the studies for non-binary people, but that doesn't mean it doesn't exist. Political correctness and a lack of funding discourage anyone from doing those studies to prove it.

This really shows the internal struggle that I think most binary trans people go through.  Recently my friend 'A' just came out as non-binary to my friend 'K' (a cis girl) and me (a transgender guy). When they did so, K mentioned how she didn't view either of us as male or female. I talked to her about it and she realized that it was rude to say that to me, but the whole situation demonstrates why traditional trans people don't always except the less traditional ones.  I think kindness is usually the best policy, but it's hard to be kind to people that misrepresent the majority of the community.  I think it wouldn't be as much of an issue if there was more of a separation between traditional and non-binary trans people. That's where the word transsexual comes in to play, as an alternative to let cis people know 'we're serious.'  On the other hand, why should we force them to be girls and guys if they don't want to be? I mean can't us 'freaks' stand up for those 'freaks?'  I think trans people who hate non-binary people are the ones with the most crippling dysphoria. So I also sympathize with them.   Non-binary people aren't inherently bad, but their intentions aren't clear to people who aren't them. I don't believe they're doing it for attention, but if it's not to alleviate dysphoria than what could it be for? I personally think that they think gender is more of a feeling and they don't feel like a gender because nobody really feels like any gender unless being the most stereotypical version of one.   Until we find out what being transgender means scientifically, I describe it as 'the overwhelming desire to physically become a different sex.' Which is why non-binary people are confusing.  I don't know what to do other than support non-binary people as well as separate myself from them to prevent confusion.  Edit: I also once thought I was non-binary about 4 years ago.  I also don't want to be a douche bag, so I'm not going to bring it up to any non-binary people. kindness is always the best policy.

I know you probably won't really see this. But... I just wanted to say that you've come a long way. Like, a really long way. I discovered you after HBomberguy's DK64 torture porn stream on twitch, and heard your delightful and heavenly voice the very first time.  Then I looked up your channel, and did what I normally do on a newly discovered tube: troll through the back log of videos (nautical trolling of the ocean floor reference, rather than internet/monster/asshole trolling)  Your soul seemed to shine through you. The topics of your videos, the pain, the struggle, all of that was so artfully and precisely put on display in a way that seemed like you had the thought of 'fuck it. If I'm going to feel like this either way, I could at least help other people.' And sure, you started out with things along the lines of 'IS GARBAGE AND THIS IS WHY' but the topics were always a lot more 'Draw steel against the flames of fascism' rather than 'this shit stinks, lol'. I felt like I wasn't being talked down to. I felt like everything you said was being presented in an interesting way, sure, but I never felt like I was being called stupid or a moron for thinking some of the things I did.    People may be drawn to your aesthetic, or criticize you for it. I think it's very important that you frame these things like this. When you're throwing a new idea at someone, an idea that uproots everything they might have thought, an idea that twists and turns AGAINST what you knew to be the prevailing winds of reason, then that feels like an attack. It's been scientifically proven. Now, attacks can be successful. You can really change things by attacking them, by damaging them. But people are a little different. People adapt, change their argument, start falling back on more and more primitive means of dodging and deflecting. Half of it isn't even in the bounds of reason. How do you undermine defenses that are built around prejudice and tradition? Hate and underlying motive? Those things are insane! They are the enemy of reason, and the blades of a man who doesn't care if he's right, just knows that he will never be wrong.  I'll tell you how to combat that kind of insanity: with your own insanity.  Your aesthetic, your wrapping paper, your delivery. It is madness. It has always been madness. It's the same madness we all feel, that horrible feeling lingering at the edge of our vision at night, that if we look just a little bit to the left of reality, we can see the abyss. That dread fear of the dark, that gnawing doubt about everything, you've taken that as a given and built a whole channel around it. People think of doubt as a horrible thing, and don't get me wrong, a lot of the time it is. But doubt is also how you pass laws against slavery. Doubt is how you write laws to protect civil liberties. When you stop taking things as granted, stop trusting in the natural or supernatural order of the world, that doubt can lead to a better and more perfect union of people who really just want to get a long.  Doubt is what lets trans people be trans, they doubt the binary gender norm. Doubt lets homosexuals fall in love and actually let that be a happy thing rather than some tragic admission of a mental disorder. Doubt is what I use every day to come to terms with the horrible abuse that I was told all the time was just fine, and you don't need to see a doctor, and don't tell your teachers how your mom really treats you-  Ugh, this is getting long and meandering.  There's a lot of bad things that indecisiveness can bring, but being indecisive is how evil people stop doing evil things. It what stops hate. And that's what you bring with your madness: the varied and satirical impossibilities and absurdities are perfect defense for the real ideas you try to impart to the most stubborn of us.  Also, you wearing a beard looks really weird. Like, in the same way that I would think it strange should my wife suddenly sport a beard. Or me for that matter, but that's different ;)

here's my theory of gender. it is not a matter of biology, psychology, or even performativity per se - it's a social role influenced by all 3. we are not born boys or girls. we are born babies, and we are then coercively assigned a gender based on our biology. we can eventually manage to change genders through performativity and often changes to our biology, and the urge to do so is caused by something in one's psychology. in every society, there will always be something in between - hjra, two-spirit, nonbinary folks who perform ambiguity, even just trans people early in transition - however, most people, regardless of psychological identity, will end up being one or the other. in my own mind, i am nonbinary, but in a practical sense, outside the internet, i am female. that is the perspective i bring to politics, to relationships, to my daily interactions with the world. that is a much better explanation than 'penis=boy vagina=girl', or than 'i'm a man/woman because i said so', or than 'anyone in a dress is a woman'.

Lol I love that 'Tiffany' is even sporting Blaire's most-worn shade of lipstick  A little on-the-nose (er, I guess, more 'on-the-lips'), but I'm not complaining.  Okay. So. I have ONE gripe with the idea of not separating non-binaryism (with dysphoria) from being gender-nonconforming (without dysphoria). (For reference, I am Agender - I go by either Dani or D.J., though close family and friends call me Jack, a holdover from when I still thought I was binary trans - pronouns They/Them.)  Now, I know you've referred to yourself as 'the Tranny 1%', Nat, so maybe this is something you just kinda overlooked. But classifying someone as trans without the prerequisite of dysphoria, and therefore demedicalising transition, causes a huge problem for broke-ass cripple bitches like me: not having GCS & HRT covered by public or private insurance (I'm in Canada, so in my case, most of it is covered by OHIP, the provincial insurance plan, and the rest by ODSP, my Disability Support insurance plan), and therefore, not being able to afford transition. Which, in America, is probably wholly expected and common, since people there apparently have to crowdfund medical expenses to just to keep their hearts beating. But to me, in my privileged little Canadian world, that's wholly inconceivable, and thoroughly unbearable to consider. It's also completely unrealistic a situation for me to overcome, since I'm not attractive, popular, or connected enough to get the attention I'd need in order to fund my transition independently.  And while yes, a good majority of trans suicides can be blamed on transphobia and preexisting mood disorders piling on top of trans troubles, I guarantee you that the inability to transition has killed some people. I do not in any way believe that dysphoria only exists because of societal expectations, otherwise, would enbies even exist at all? Well, I guess that's technically debatable. But I can tell you that, for me personally, not being able to transition would kill me, and not because I care whether *other* people find me aesthetically pleasing in an androgynous sort of way. I care whether *I* think I look aesthetically pleasing in an androgynous sort of way. And while I'm not quite ready to start dieting and exercising to fully rid myself of the non-sex-characteristic-based dysphoria, I'm at least relieved partway by the treatment I've managed to procure so far. If I couldn't get to that treatment because I was poor, then... I probably wouldn't even be here commenting this, right now.  So yes, I DO agree with about 95% of the arguments you make here, and as usual, it was wildly entertaining and high in production quality (also, loving the cybergoth character, just as an aside). But class struggles - which you DID mention in passing when you noted that some trans people can't afford to transition, but didn't really expand on any further - are a central reason, as far as I'm concerned, why - at least for now - transition needs to stay medicalised, at LEAST in part. Like your argument in the Gender Critical episode about certain Abolitionist movements targeting the most vulnerable of a demographic instead of the most privileged, so too does this problem exist within the transmed vs anti-transmed debate. If the first people it would most severely negatively affect are some of the most hard done by in society, imo, you're doing social justice wrong.

I honestly think that so called 'transtrenders' are actually a good sign because it means that this whole queer project is working. The purpose of queering spaces is to question and break down the norms and social pressures that keep people from living their lives authentically. People being comfortable enough to openly question their own gender and play with their expression in new and unique ways is kinda the end goal of the whole movement. Gender isn't static and it's to complex for us to demand people conform to rigid ideas of how one can live in their own bodies and what language they can use to convey their experiences. Its doing Cis, trans, and nonbinary folk a disservice to police their gender.  So I personally welcome all stargender, maverique, genderfaun, genderflux, genderfluid, bigender, agender, genderqueer, demigender and all other non-binary folks who just want to be themselves, and make it a little easier for everyone else to do the same.

I feel like there's this wonderful thing about non-binary genders that is so damn appealing. I think the idea of seeing someone that openly identifies as nb feels confusing to many people because they simply never thought of nb identities in such a way. Most people would be lying if they haven't wondered the things they could have as the opposite gender, and even if gender didn't exist. Human's are jealous creatures, and it really is a shame that we put people in categories that presume certain characteristics from an individual that may or may not really be there, and these presumptions are then followed up by placing societal constraints.   I am currently struggling with my gender identity, as I was born a female and raised as one. Yet, it is not physical gender dysphoria that troubles me, but an adolescence that kept me from acting a certain way. I've come to loathe many of the things that society pushes onto women, like feminine fashion, marriage, raising children, etc. But I do not completely want to get rid of those things. I still like many of the things the female gender has to offer, probably more than that of male. Nb identity feels more like both acknowledging the existence of God, yet rejecting their authority, at least from my point of view.   I guess what I'm saying is that nb-ism is just a big 'fuck you' to the social constructs that have placed people into so many boxes. I feel like as a cis woman this is easy to say, but I fear that these societal gender roles harm much more than just the feelings of little girls like myself. I fear that men don't have the voice to say these things and that trans women, like in your video, are afraid to say because of the fear that they wouldn't be valid (and that goes for men too).   I guess I'm just saying that I would like to transition, but it's not that I'm fearful (maybe a little about what friends and family would think), it's mostly that I wonder if I'm valid enough to do so. Does being simply disillusioned with society grant a special pass for me to chose the gender I want? However, I guess I don't mind what gender I am perceived as, because I'm the end I value more what makes me feel good rather than what makes me valid in society's eyes. And I'd love to make people mad and confused too

Because I knew I felt more like a boy than a girl, so, this was probably it, right? So I held in every ounce of my femininity to fit the trans guy social role, and got way more acceptance than when I was a genderfluid person. And then, I went to an actual gender therapist and they told me 'Hey, why did you come out as a trans man?' And I said the truth 'I didn't feel acceptance when I was out as genderfluid.' And then I realised how that sounded. I was actually considering going on T when I grew up. And if I did, I would actually have dysphoria and de-transition. So it was not SJW propaganda that made me a 'transtrender', it was the truscum community. I did everything I could to prove to them that I was 100% boy, to prove to them that I have gender dysphoria, that I convinced myself that I did have it.
