I love everything you do, which is why I want to address one question you left me with. Why did you let that point about argument against performativity theory stand ('actors playing women being just as much a woman as a trans woman')? An actor and a trans woman are both performing gender, that's true, but actors have an entire additional layer to their performance:  the social contract of the stage. They are attempting to convince us of something we know to be false, as per the request of the audience. People in daily lives have no such social contract. In fact, performativity purports to explain validity and so consenting entertainment (actors in dresses playing women) seems outside the scope of Butler's argument. I feel like dysphoria is very real, mostly because I experience it, but is far from an adequate test for 'gatekeeping' purposes as to whether someone is 'really' trans (because for instance a lot of people have autism, but not everyone with autism is nonverbal).   I feel like I'm being erased when someone wants to claim my dysphoria is all a matter of my self esteem and I can't sleep some days or even weeks of my life because of how wrong my body feels. But I think that having dysphoria and being a woman are different things. It's interesting to note there's a similar kind of conflict in the autism community between people who need assistance to get by and people who are fighting for respect in society over whether it's a disorder or just a different kind of neurotype. I can't really speak for the autism community as I'm still kind of on the edges of it (I was referred to someone to get diagnosed, but never got around to finishing the process. I have some executive difficulties and maybe some sensory ones to do with sound and pretty bad anxiety. So ok, probably autism but, respectfully... well. I dunno, that may be waiting on a medical gatekeeper with the same kind of flawedness. But I'm new at thinking of myself that way so I'm hesitant to speak, you know?) - but I suspect with the trans community the answer is yes, and. I suspect there's a reasonable flock of medical things that may cause dysphoria and that some trans people identify as women because, among other things, their somatic dysphoria but I also suspect there's a flock of social and psychological causes as well and I'm not convinced that a biological cause is 'better' than a social cause when it comes to an umbrella that could be big enough for everyone if we'd just let it.

I'm AFAB, non-binary, very femme looking, but act quite masculine. As a little kid I refused to be a girl, but once I hit puberty, boobs and hips made me fairly unmistakably feminine. Yet I always felt like I was in drag wearing female clothes, and I even often exaggerated my femininity in presentation because of it. I did bind my boobs for a while, and often wished I looked more androgynous, but as the years passed, I learned to be more accepting of my presentation.   After years of being a trans ally (though I had no interest in medically transitioning, I could easily place myself in the mind of those who felt they needed to confirm their gender), and hearing more and more people come out as trans and non-binary, I finally accepted the label non-binary. I am generally very non-conformist, but I am also 43, and not in need of much attention. My flamboyant style and good looks used to garner me all kinds of attention when I was younger, and I am honestly elated that I can now walk down the street without people harassing me, hitting on me, or trying to tell me that it's not Halloween. People tend to not even really see me, and  I love it.   Today I was explaining to someone why it is unlikely that trans folx are 'just doing it for the attention.' First of all, negative attention is not like negative publicity: it doesn't really do us any good. I'm not a brand or a product, I have nothing to sell. But my feelings do get hurt when people call me names. When I used to dress all crazy-like, it was for two reasons: keep away lots of dudes (who were generally intimidated by my hyper-sexualized appearance) and to advertise to the other freaks that I was around. And a little to fuck with people's heads.     And that's perhaps the thing. The only 'attention' I am looking to garner as an enby is not the attention directed at me. It is to fuck with people's heads. I want people to question their gender assumptions. That's why I am loud and proud right now. I could have continued my journey being stealth, letting only my intimate friends know that I don't feel like a woman. I don't really care about what the world thinks of me anymore. I don't really care about the pronouns people use (though I do enjoy getting called Glenn instead of Glenda, but not enough to go around correcting people). My point is that while I have always had these feelings of being some sort of alien that never fit into the neat boxes of gender (and most likely wanted to be a man so as not to suffer the many iniquities our society visits upon women--I was brought up in a very feminist lefty household), my main reason to be out and loud about is for it to be a political act. I want people to question gender. I want people to look at me and be confused when I tell them I'm not a woman. I want to have the dialogue and the discomfort that comes with it.   This is turning into a very bad first draft of an essay. I'm rambling. I really enjoyed the video, thank you, Natalie, for continuing to churn out amazing, thoughtful content.

I don't think striving for a scientific theory to validate the identity of people is a good thing... interesting: why is this even necessary? because rational-sciencehumping-society? However I think one can account for 'trans-phenomenon' with modern meta-psychodynamics (routed in psychoanalysis). According to this (if used adequately) all forms of gender (and sexual preferences) are created by an INTERACTION of biological, psychological and societal 'factors'. This interaction varies individually and culturally which is why there are many forms of gender and sexuality. However this doesn't validate or devalidate trans. Science, if understood properly, is actually incapable of giving or taking value to anything; it's all just phenomena. But maybe it implicitly valuates in relation: if cis-males, Tiffany, Justine, Tabby and Maryland are all just different phenomena built of the same building blocks in different quantities and arrangements, then there's no reason to devalue anybody. Saying that something is more 'real' because its a diagnosable psychological disease makes no scence. In the end if something is a psych-desease or not is decided by cultural standards and if there is enough suffering involved, not by biological markers. So all Tiffany does is saying, that she's suffered and society decided to include her suffering in the DSM, which is fine, but does it actually validate/devalue her identity? Maybe Tiffany has suffered more than Tabby or Maryland. Maybe suffering is also crucial to identity. But if suffering is the only thing that validates an identity then people in first world countries have generally weaker identities than ppl in third world countries. That's my opinion. If you disagree: I'm open for discussion.

in my opinion, the existence of nonbinary identity doesnt invalidate the '2 genders' claim. 'man' and 'woman' are social constructs based on social and behavioral norms in a given society. to be nonbinary is to express qualities of either gender, or neither gender. nonbinary identity is indeed relevant to the gender discussion, i consider it a valid identity. however, i believe that the abscence/presence of both genders does not constitute a unique gender.   regarding the notion that you need dysphoria to be trans, i can somewhat have an open mind if someone were to tell me that, even without the dysphoria, transitioning would be undoubtedly important for that person. because this discussion brings about the question 'if you dont have gender dysphoria, then why do you need to transition?' transition is a fundamentally life-changing process that is irreversible if implemented surgically. so there would have to be a benefit to transitioning as opposed to not. what i mean is, would not transitioning be healthy for a given person? perhaps they dont have dysphoria, but would they be more mentally healthy if they did identify as trans? if there isnt any reason to suggest that transitioning would be good for em, then why do they need it? thats essentially where the whole idea of transtrenders comes from.   i understand that you dont believe there needs to be a reason to be...yourself. but you can easily define who you are based on who you arent. if you're in a state of being who you arent, then that implies a need to transition to become who you are. Jake must become Jackie because she is not Jake.  if you are already who you are, then why would you need to change? if Tim doesnt need to become Tiffany, then why would he want to?   overall, i think the most important aspect that defines the need to transition is time. it takes time to figure yourself out. it takes time to reach a conclusion that a given person is trans. not gender dysphoria. time. it takes time to make such a big, serious decision about your life. without time, big life decisions may potentially become fleeting. like a fad.

There was a comment I lost track of, so I'll just respond in its own thread, about 'What makes you FEEL your gender?' And speaking as a computer nerd bibliophile RPG fan who also happens to be a cis male, I generally feel male when I'm talking to other people in person who treat me as male. That's about it.  When I was younger, I thought it just a good exercise in imagination to just be able to assume a woman's point of view in books or RPGs when those were the characters whose stories I followed.  I generally don't identify my gender online, and if someone assumes my gender incorrectly (which happens surprisingly often if you just have a female cartoon character avatar or dare to back a feminist side of an argument), I've never felt a reason to correct them.  Of all the things I believe about myself, gender is one of the least important to me.  If asked to describe myself, I'd much rather talk about my talents, my interests, or what I do or have done than gender, since describing myself as 'male' seems so unhelpful.  Descriptions are for narrowing down possibilities, and saying I'm male is like being asked where my car is parked and saying 'in the northern hemisphere', since it narrows me down to half the population of Earth.     And no, none of this is to 'claim' a status as non-binary or anything 'to be special', I accept being generally treated as male, it's just that I don't understand the sheer level of hostility around the whole concept of gender to start with.  (And I also don't mean to belittle anyone who has to struggle to actually be identified the way they desire by any means, or say I can't understand why someone who has to overcome some oppression because of their background would incorporate that as part of their personal identity.  That said, I think declaring yourself 'feminist' is more important than declaring yourself 'woman', even if the latter is what formed your path to the former.)    I remember seeing all these polls in forums for computer RPGs like Elder Scrolls, and only about 40% of players would be willing to play the other gender, even in a single-player game where there's nobody there to give you shit for being a girl in a game.  When I started talking about it and why people were so wrapped up in the fragility of their identities, I would invariably be shouted down by a chorus of people who couldn't conceive of what was wrong with the 40% of players willing to 'degrade themselves' by playing a character of another gender (well, OK, so they were assuming it was men playing women, because women players don't exist... or at least admit they do if they don't want to take shit for it).  I even had one guy claim to be a doctor telling me how wrong it was for me to act like gender wasn't such a big deal because he tells patients that have testosterone insensitivity syndrome that they have the wrong gender until they CRY!  (Which just makes me wonder... what the hell is wrong with this guy?  You're so caught up in the CHROMOSOMAL DETERMINISM of gender that you'll yell at patients that they're wrong for not being a gender they've never tried to be until they cry just to satisfy HIS idea of gender conformity?!)     I also get the sense it has something to do with how we view 'the other gender' as well.... Maybe it's that I was born to a feminist mother, and I've generally adopted positive female role-models, grew up having friends that were girls and traded Transformers for My Little Ponys, and been willing to take shit defending feminism that I'm not too scared of being called a girl?  I get the sense a part of it is a fear/disdain/hatred of 'the other side' that drives the all-consuming existential terror that someone might think a male has 'feminine' traits.  Why would it be an insult, otherwise?  Why are men scared to play woman characters even in RPGs around a tabletop with people they know or in single-player computer games if they didn't find it inherently demeaning?

It would be interesting what the reasons that some persons end up being transmedicalists are. I think that this whole gatekeeping thing contributes really much to this whole concept of transmedicalism. As was mentioned with Tiffany as an example, the whole identity as a transgender person is based arround the diagnosis of gender dysphoria. But under what circumstances does someone get this diagnosis (of gender dysphoria) in the first place?     Most countries are very gatekeepy, which means that in order to get medical treatment the patient has to go through a whole bunch of tests to prove that he/she/they is trans. This process can be very traumatizing because one has to (!) disclose personal experiences one would not even want to tell to their diary. But they have to do this to get the label 'true trans' from the doctors in order to get the medical treatment like hormones. Not just that, but real life experience tests as part of the gatekeeping can also be very traumatizing while at the same time they do not really contribute anything valuable to whole pre-medical transition process.     It is understandable (for me) that the trans patient, in order to cope with the traumatizing process, is beginning to identify with it and its absolute goal. Which means that the whole identity and therefore most of the self-consciousness of a person gets tied to the diagnosis of gender dysphoria. After all the pain one had to go through, not only the pain of gender dysphoria, but also the pain of the diagnosis-process, this diagnosis will be held high to the sky as the sign that it is done. Maybe one has invested very much (life-)time to get this very important diagnosis just to get the much needed medical treatment. Persons who don't experience dysphoria but are also in some sort part of the trans community are therefore classified as not valid, because they don't go through the agonizing diagnosis-process.   If this whole unnecessary gatekeeping process wouldn't exist maybe there wouldn't be a concept of transmedicalism which is used inside the trans community to prove who is really trans and valid and who isn't. What are your thoughts? Am I interpreting too much in this whole concept?

Damn, did Natalie really prove a huge point here? Like goodness, I never thought of the way I've actually been treating other trans people. I kinda feel like a dick now for being so invalidating to trans people that I didn't recognize as 'the norm'. Huh.

Gender is biological AND psychological/behavioral AND social. However, biology influences psychology/behavior and social interactions but is only influenced marginally in return (e.g. when social interaction modifies hormonal levels). Psychology/Behavior and social interactions strongly influence each other.  There is an argument to be made, that a lot of the push back experienced by transgender/non-binary people stems from the fact that they try to directly influence their social gender, when that part of the identity is created by the interplay with other people. You can directly modify your behavior and sexual identity (from a psychological point of view) and through medical intervention can modify your biological identity - that's for you alone to decide. The social aspect, however, is constructed in collaboration with other people - and their reactions can be different from what you imagine. That's where 'passing' actually plays an important part if you are aiming for consistent male or female identity - and for most adults those two are the only genders they can help to construct a priori. While I'm sympathetic to the fact, that a mismatch between the social and the psychological/biological gender causes dissonance, it's not for the trans-person to decide the behavior of others as it's not for the others to decide the behavior of a trans-person.

Miss Contrapoints, thanks for another excellent video. I don't always agree with you but you've definitely made me look at things from different perspectives. For one I will definitely be more patient with people, especially teenagers trying to figure out their gender. Such an important decision as transitioning must take time, unless we want a ton of detransitioners as a result of very young people, or just adults whom are in a bad place in life making those decisions on a whim. I think you need to live for at least a year as the gender you believe fits you before even thinking of such things as hormones and corrective surgeries.  I do however absolutely disagree with you about the definition of trans = being displeased about your societal role. I believe that kind of thinking is damaging as it pretty much goes against everything feminism has been working for since the very beginning of the movement. When I think about societal roles it involves everything from what you're wearing and your body language to wether you prefer to be a stay at home parent or a breadwinner (to clearify I don't think anyone of those is superior to the other).  While I do believe some personality traits are more feminine or masculine than others, such as women in general being more nurturing (as much as many will hate me for saying this) I hate the idea that anyone who happens to posses traits not expected of their sex should be considered trans. Not to mention that some gender roles, as most CP-fans can probably agree with me on are pretty damn harmful, such as equating femininity with submissiveness (something that I will subscribe to over my dead body).  It really worries me that some trans women seems to believe that they need to be obedient, extremely soft-spoken and meek in order to be accepted as women, and I really understand that this interpretation angers and frustrates cis-women who've been trying to break out of those roles for ages.  I guess I'd fall under the definition of transmed since I believe that being trans is all about feeling a disconnect with the body you were born with, even though I do believe that that disconnect can vary from person to person.  One person may feel satisfied with hormonal therapy while one may need to go through all corrective surgeries to alleviate their dysphoria.  To clarify, I do believe that you need dysphoria to be trans but I also believe that the struggle of non-binary people is very real. In fact I even believe that non-binary is a necessary label for certain trans people who like Ash Hardell for example only needed top-surgery to alleviate their dysphoria as well as intersex people who feel perfectly comfortable identifying that way.  No matter what though I do agree with you that patience and compassion is important,  and that we should show the people who are still trying struggling with their identity respect. Being a teenager or in general out of balance is hard enough as it is without the rest of us being well... shitgibbons about it :).  PS. I apologize to anyone who reads this if some of my points are unclear. There is so much more I want to say, but this post has literally taken me hours to write and I feel that it's going to take me all day if I continue. May add to it more later :)

I think one of the things that's helpful to me in this context is figuring out what the harm will be if [group] does [thing].  In this context, let's say that some number of people identify as trans or nonbinary at some point but ultimately decide that they aren't.  What harm will be caused?  Well, some of those individuals may go through medical procedures that they later want to reverse and that may leave some side-effects.  Some people will see them as evidence that trans and/or nonbinary people don't really exist.  (Though, IMO, there's an awfully big overlap between people who would interpret it that way and people who privately doubted trans and/or nonbinary people existed to begin with.)  But, telling them they're wrong to explore will likely hurt people who really are trans and/or nonbinary, depriving them of any room to explore that.  It also hurts the movement as a whole by dividing it against itself, which really only benefits people who want to deny rights to trans and NB folks.  I think different parts of the conversation should be led by different people.  A person who hasn't experienced gender dysphoria probably shouldn't be leading the conversation about transitioning for the purpose of alleviating gender dysphoria.  (In the same way, I, as a childless-by-choice woman, shouldn't be leading the conversation about providing better maternity leave.  I can be an ally of course, but I shouldn't lead the conversation about it.)  Conversely, the conversation about being nonbinary or genderqueer should probably be led by people who experience that, rather than people who are trans but identify solely as male or female.  I think the challenge often comes in that through some mix of privilege, luck, and platform, it's really common for some members of a community to end up with the platform to talk about certain issues which they don't really experience.  For instance, I first heard about non-binary people through a video made by a queer producer talking about gender and sexuality, but who wasn't nonbinary herself.  That in and of itself isn't bad--but it can sometimes lead to many people knowing about a particular thing only from others talking about that thing, and not from the people who are that thing.

I have read a medical study, some time ago, that actually validated all genders, including non-binary and agender, stemming from the gendered brain theory. The argument was that white matter patterns vary greatly between individuals. Sure, trans women and cis women present very similar patterns amongst themselves, that differ violently from trans/cis male patterns, and viceversa. But those are just the two ends of the spectrum. A virtually endless variety of intermediate patterns exists (I mean, have you ever considered how complex the brain is?), and consequently, a virtually endless variety of genders, made only more complex by the intersections with the separate but contiguous parameters of sexual orientation, and gender expression. This conception highlights dramatically, in my opinion, how devastatingly stupid it is to reduce all of human experience to two genders and one sexual orientation. Sure, as Natalie says, who cares about your brain, no one has ever seen it. But to some degree, scientific validation may be useful and helpful to those who are still trying to figure out their place in the spectrum , or have already done so but find themselves ostracized by our society. I'm a cis woman, so if I'm over-medicalizing the trans experience I apologize, but I find these discoveries utterly fascinating and don't think they will necessarily narrow down our visions on gender, if anything they will widen them. And I can't help but feel like it would be a shame not to make the facts-don't-care-about-your-feelings crowd face the reality of science being on gender-non-conforming people's side.

Since it was such a big question in the video, I feel compelled to share what led me to 'believe in' transgender being a thing.  I've never felt much like my gender myself, so my conclusion was that it didn't really exist. Much like a TERFs I believed gender was completely a social construct and I fought long and hard to not be defined or constricted by my gender.   I didn't understand how to combine this world view with trans people, because the concept of trans people relies on gender being real and valid and important, and that kinda what I was fighting against. Or at least that what I thought, I guess in retrospect I guess I was fighting against sex being constructive. I didn't realize the difference between sex and gender at this point.  A few things changed it for me. First I heard I podcast with radiolab about a person who'd switch gender unvulentarily from moment to moment. They could walk into the shower and feel fine about being a man, but switch before they walked out of the shower and experience crushing disphoria when they saw themselves in the mirror. They changed mannerisms, to a degree where other people could tell the difference. They lost their wife in this process, though they were still good friends.  I dunno. Hearing about this, hearing a person experiencing this shift in gender, and some scientists confirming it.. It made me think that there's something about gender being real. That apparently there *is* something in the brain that perceives itself as man or woman. It's not just a construct, there is more to it.  Years went by and I stumbled upon first non-binary and then trans youtubers. Hearing their experiences further confirmed to me that, though I don't feel attached to my gender, it really is important to some other people. I remember the Shit trans people say video where they describe, jokingly, dreading injecting a needle into themselves every day. Fuck. Y'know.. That's tough! If you're willing to do that to yourself, even though it's super uncomfortable, there's a reason, y'know?   It reminds me of people realizing being gay being real and not a choice when a gay person asked them 'Why would I choose this? I can't get married, I was excluded from my community why would I choose this?'  After I'd watch trans youtubers explain how important their gender was to them, I started asking my friends about their gender. Like, I feel like I'd be fine with being called 'he'. But my somewhat conservative when it comes to gender roles, male friend that I talked to said he'd feel uncomfortable being called she. He asked what it was like for me to not feel like that. And my quite sjw female friend said she wouldn't be comfortable being called he.  Well shit. Gender is real. It's just a spectrum. Some people, like my friends, really do feel uncomfortable not being recognized as their gender. I just don't. It doesn't have to either be real or not real, it can be important for some and not others.  I've realized that that doesn't make neither I, nor cis people attached to their gender, nor trans people invalid. Gender is important for some people, less for others, regardless, sex shouldn't have to define you. But if it makes you more comfortable acting in a gender conforming way because it confirms your gender to those around you, that's okay. It's just also okay not to, and people shouldn't be forced to act in a certain way. Gender and gender expression is different, and it's possible to fight for the right to gender and gender expression and against restrictive and forced upon gender expressions as well. We don't have to fight against each other, it's possible to fight for all.  Damn. I'm writing this on my phone on a festival, I'm sorry for the format and repetition. I have a hard time editing it.  My point is. I wasn't convinced through facts or stats or performance. I was convinced by conversation and representation. Just like so many people have with being gay. It's real. I don't know why or how, wtf is sexuality, but there's been so many reports that there's no doubt in my mind that homosexuality is real. And now, with more exposure, I feel the same with transgender and gender in general. It's real. There is enough people reporting it that I can't imagine it not being real.  Puh. That was a lot. But I hope my story might be an insight into how it a possible to convince people of the validity and realness of these subjects.

A few points about performativity and psychological reasons for gender.  1. On the argument about drag queens and screen actors playing different genders and if they're trans because they're performing, isn't there a difference between performing socially and performing for entertainment? Drag queens and actors don't necessarily live their lives as non-binary or women or men, they perform temporarily for entertainment. Doesn't performative theory differentiate between that and performing socially, living one's life as a binary or non-binary gender?   2. The difference between psychologically 'feeling' as a certain gender and 'feeling' as a Norwegian cat, for example, is that gender is uniquely human (as BaBooTube Videos pointed out in another comment). So just cause you feel like a cat, you can't psychologically be a cat cause you're human. The same for attack helicopter or whatever strawman joke transphobes like coming up with. So they psychological aspect (or 'theory') is certainly valid.   3.  Why does Justine say gender could be social OR psychological? (I'm ignoring biological here) Isn't there a connection between social roles people are expected to perform and the psychological impact they might have? Even language (pronouns) is a social construct and if one psychologically cannot identify with a certain set of pronouns (he/him or she/her) due to the social implications of said pronouns, one can choose a neutral pronoun they're comfortable with. That's a psychological impact of a social structure.   That being said, you're right. There is no need for any theory (social, biological or psychological) to prove the validity and existence of all trans people. You're all valid and all deserve headpats and rights! One thing that I am curious about when it comes to non-binary identities is how people choose to define why they're non-binary. Often times I see people defining themselves as non-binary based on the feeling that they don't fit their assigned gender. This interests me particularly because I have come to the conclusion that gender is socially constructed insofar as it describes a set of socially expected behaviors. Some of those expected behaviors may be biologically informed but that doesn't mean they all have to be. As an example, there are social expectations and pressures exerted on men to not express emotions, to be breadwinners, to be protectors, and even to be aggressive. These behaviors are now recognized as being potentially harmful to men; they're labeled toxic masculinity and there is now a movement to redefine the expected norms to exclude expectations of potentially negative behaviors and to include a broader range of expression from men.   This brings me to my question; based on what criteria exactly are people deciding that they don't 'fit' their assigned gender? If gender is essentially a set of stereotypes perpetuated by social expectation, it seems to me that defining yourself as not identifying with the gender stereotypes and therefore not that gender is legitimizing that a gender should be defined by the current stereotypes and social expectations. Particularly in the case of men, this seems counter-productive to the project of ending negative stereotypes.   All of that admittedly leaves me in a weird place because I believe that despite my own feelings about what makes someone a 'legitimate' trans/nb person, it's not my place to lay those judgements on others. I'm also pretty sure there are legitimate reasons for someone to identify as non-binary instead of pushing for broader norms within their assigned gender identity despite not being able to personally conceive of such a reason myself.   On another note, another point of concern for me when it comes to the transtrender debate that I don't feel was really addressed in this video is that there seems to be a social aspect to being trans that goes beyond what you'd expect based on just wider acceptance. Young people are especially more likely to come out as trans when one or more of their peers do. There is also the phenomenon of gay boys believing they are trans until they determine they're actually gay. A lot of this also seems to be mediated by online talking points that are, to put it lightly, less than nuanced when it comes to the discussion of what it means to be trans. This is where I think your argument about trans-medicalism should work great and that not expecting people to medically transition would alleviate the problem of mass numbers of young people needlessly transitioning, but that doesn't seem to be the common narrative among young people and there is a growing contingent of people who advocate that not allowing children to transition is a form of child abuse.   Would love to hear anyone's thoughts on the above issues and if you think I've been ignorant in some way. Much love and peace.

I relate intensely to the main takeaway - you don't need logic to justify your identity. You are who you are. I mean, I don't really know who I am anymore because every signifier of my identity I held onto has slipped away, leaving only an empty rote performance of what people expect from me that crumbles a tiny bit every day, and a series of habits I'm too tired and anxious to get rid of. and I know who I would like to be but there's a nagging voice saying that's not who I am, that I'm just trying to run away from myself. Except if that were true why is what I think I want a recurring theme going back to childhood? but I've been running into that demand for logic and reason - I need a pile of proof that I am what I think I might be. I need detailed observation, I need data, I need evidence, I need ARGUMENTS.   Sometimes it's creepy how much Natalie's different characters reflect my conflicting thoughts. Tiffany Tumbles is a lot like the recurring thoughts in my head telling me I'm not, it's just online exposure, it's just a fetish, I could never do it. and, damn, Baltimore does make me uncomfortable. I support and would defend nonbinary people forever, but my brain doesn't work that way. I don't GET it. I accept and love, but the psychology eludes me on a purely emotional level. and it doesn't work for my problems. I wish it did! But the ambiguity terrifies me. But Baltimore is mostly right. I think Natalie makes them purposefully a bit off-putting on a performance level, to not tip the scales too much, but it's still pretty clear - at least this is probably what would be healthy for us to believe, if nothing else. Everything else fucks us up worse one way or another, from transmedicalism to performative theory to biology. Better to just shrug, throw up our hands, and say 'yeah, this is who I am, no I don't really get it either, your guess is as good as mine, but I'm still valid dammit'.   anyway, back to logic, and to justification. When you think about it, it's an absurd thing to have to justify your identity. You justify your position on issues, on art (if you want to, it's optional), on the weather. but on you? nobody in the fucking world knows you except you. If you're wrong about yourself, you're also the only one that can say that for certain. You can choose to take advice from other people, especially if you discover your internal monologue is self-destructive and leads you to self-harm, but even when you're telling lies to yourself about yourself, you kinda know who you are anyway, when you get past a certain age. If you're twisted up, doing a performance, not being real....somewhere in your awareness you know what's up. and if you're a kid you haven't even had the time to develop an elaborate series of defense mechanisms, so yeah, it's even more bullshit to say kids don't know what they are.   I mean, I know the truth about me. I have no idea what that truth will look like, when it comes out. but I know now that I'm not going to worry so much about providing a set of justifications to people. and if they ask me, did I always know....of course. But the problem was, I was treated as very smart because of my early developed verbal ability, and I learned too early that things should make sense. Things should have rational justifications. maybe it should have been some kind of clue to me that I was bad at math early on - logic....wasn't actually my strong suit. I was a circular peg shoved into a square hole. I let binaries govern my thinking, because everything seemed scary and chaotic (everything still does, I perceive reality in a really disordered, hazy way, I think, which REALLY doesn't lend itself well to playing the Smart Boy.   I need the Baltimore mindset - my feeling of myself is valid, the things I want are valid, my feelings about every aspect of me are valid, and their validity is axiomatic. It's Cartesian, cogito ergo sum, bitches. I start with the assumption I know me, and from there, the world.

This video really speaks to me. I was out as a transwoman for nearly a full decade and I was every bit the Blair White stereotype. I would throw other people/groups whom I deemed 'weirder' than myself under the bus amongst friends because I was desperate to be accepted for myself. I've always been pretty feminine, but I also felt like I was trapped in a sociological cage because I was constrained to acting feminine in order to maintain my 'transness'.   Your videos make a huge difference, contra. Voices like yours are what helped me to realize that the social problem isn't non-binary individuals, or just transwomen who go a day without shaving every part of their body (because let's be honest, for some of us it's a full time job)  - the problem is the people who can't accept that everyone really is different. We come in all shapes and sizes, with unique temperaments, personalities, and so on, and not only is it impossible to separate us out into neat little boxes like 'he' and 'she', it's also ultimately pointless. The only way we can change things is to be out there and exist.  Anyway, I identify as non-binary which I guess means I have the distinction of being able to say I was the 'self hating tran'. Heck that. I'm out, I'm proud to be who I am, and I'm happy to be able to say I love and appreciate people for who they are and the things that make them unique. Keep up the good work, all of you - that means those of you in the comments, too, whether you're actively producing content or just existing as the awesome people you are out there in the real world. <3

I ran into some hardcore gatekeepers when I was first questioning my gender identity in my early twenties, and basically swallowed a bunch of ideas that were going around on Livejournal at the time like, if you were REALLY trans you'd want to be super masc, if you were REALLY trans then you would be suicidal from gender dysphoria/completely non-functional... I was (and still am) really into BL/yaoi comics, and back then there was this attitude of 'you're not really trans, you just read too much BL and think you want to be a bishie' which like...knowing what I know now about just how many BL/slash fans are trans...  Maybe we're attracted to male/male comics about pretty androgynous boys BECAUSE we're trans!! ever think of that, huh??  Anyway my point is that being treated like a trans trender drove me away from exploring my gender identity and into a period of trying to force myself to be as femme as possible for like 7-8 years and it made me miserable as fuck. 'Guess I can't be trans, I have to be a woman now' --me, circa 2013. And now here I am over 30 and old and just starting to figure out my shit, and I keep having fantasies of like 'what if I had explored this stuff when I was fucking 15 instead of now.' Kids now have SO much more leeway to explore trans identity, I'm jealous as fuck. I didn't even know non-binary was a thing. When I was a teenager I had people dribbling poison in my ear like 'just because you want to be a guy doesn't mean you're trans' (literally people said that).  And now with the purity politics going around Tumblr and fandom spaces...there's a certain crowd that says if you're a woman writing m/m erotic content, you're like, fetishizing gay men or whatever the shit (it's bullshit seriously), and if you try to explain like no, this has always been an expression of gender identity for me, you'll get accused of not being a real tran. Because, of course, a real tran would medically transition. See here URL for the kind of bullshit people say about m/m fiction all the time. Popular m/m author says they're trans or changes their mind about their identity, everyone accuses them of being a fake. Ugh. Add that to the 'bisexual isn't really queer' attitude and we have a full house.  There absolutely needs to be a space for being confused. I avoided queer spaces all my life because I always felt I wasn't 'queer enough.' I'm not 'really trans' (NB don't real), not really gay (bisexuality doesn't count amirite), but I don't feel comfortable living a straight cis life, either. So I lived my fantasies through fiction and writing. I'm an anti-SJW, and I've been a fan of yours for a while. I think people should be whoever they want to be and dress however they want to dress, but I also think things that can be explained rationally, should be explained rationally. I found myself agreeing far more with Tiffany Tumbles, even though she's obviously made to be dislikeable. The way I see it, there's nothing wrong with not conforming to a binary of gender roles, but that's different from being 'transgender' in the sense that you have gender dysphoria. I see it as two issues being grouped into one, and oversimplified. I think what the world needs is more clarity because transgender people only look crazy when there are multiple conflicting identities shoved under one umbrella. Being gender dysphoric, as I understand it, is a psychological condition. I agree with 'Tiffany Tumbles' that this is a mental disorder, simply on the basis that the issues that come with it cannot be solved entirely through social acceptance, but that being functional with this condition requires treatment (i.e. gender reassignment surgery, hormones, etc.). 'Disease' is, unfortunately, stigmatized, but calling it a condition or disorder, I think, is only rational, since it causes problems regardless of cultural context. 'Transtrenders,' I think, refers to people who simply don't align with gender roles & stereotypes, which I deem to be a mixture of biological and cultural. For instance, a man who wears a dress, or a woman who relates more to men and spends far more time with them, or, on the very slight end of the spectrum, a woman who would rather take a more dominant role in her partnership, and take a job while her husband stays at home. These are all things that defy gender roles, but they are not gender dysphoria, because the problems that come with these things can all be solved completely by societal acceptance of individuals. As all individuals are different, whether gender roles are social or biological, there will always be outliers to the gender norms, and by extension, everyone will be somewhere on that spectrum. People who present themselves with nonbinary gender roles may face societal scrutiny in more traditional settings, but it's not the same thing as having gender dysphoria, which is why I think it should be called something different than 'Transgender.' Ultimately, I think making this umbrella of acceptance so wide is just confusing, grouping transexuals, homosexuals, and gender-queers into the same group of LGBTQ+, when I don't think transgenderism is a gay issue, and I don't think gender nonconformism  is a trans issue. I think they're totally different things, hardly even related. Sure, I think everyone should feel free to express themselves how they want, and I also believe everyone's somewhere on the queer spectrum--but that doesn't mean there's 76 different genders, nor do I think that means there are infinite genders, because if we're talking about 'gender' in the context of transmedicalism, and the prevailing notion is that there's a notable difference between male and female brains, then that necessitates two genders. I think everyone should be more accepting, but also talk about this stuff more rationally because when it's reduced to feelings, it loses its respectability.

I can't help but feel like Justine and Tiffany's conversation approached its logical conclusion, but never actually arrived there. Justine was so close when she compared gender to loving one's children, but then abandoned the line of thought... Gender isn't biological, psychological, or socially constructed--but it can be examined through those lenses. I think (and please argue with me if you feel otherwise because I want to hear other opinions on this) it really just comes down to radical subjectivity. You scrutinize deeper and deeper until terms like 'male' and 'female' become absurd categories without any meaningful distinguishing parameters--it's just an expression of pure subjectivity; a something out of nothing; the Cartesian cogito. I think it's time to ditch the Judith Butler and hop onto Lacan and Stirner. 'Il n'y a pas de relation sexuel'. Lacan posits that the basis of 'hysteria' (in the psychoanalytic sense of the word) is essentially a radical questioning of interpellation (i.e., calling into question the ways in which one is made into a subject by various forms of social authority). The hysteric asks, 'Why am I what you say I am?'. Well, I think it only makes sense for gender expression (particularly in the case of queer or non-cishet) to be the 'hysterical' affirmation of one's subjectivity: 'I am what I am because I feel like I am and I say that I am, and fuck you if you don't like it. I don't owe you an explanation. I don't need to justify myself.'

There really are biological bases for both gender and sexuality, this has even been demonstrated in mice and other mammals. It's not 'male' and 'female' brains, it's a specific brain region that is responsible for mating behavior. One part of mating behavior is who you are attracted to, and the other is how you act to get a partner. And yes humans have built whole gender roles out of that cause well, we're really good at making shit up. There are biological basis for everything, I mean, we are our brains. And yeah that includes a parents love for their child (it's oxytocin, among other things). Evolutionary psychology is all about this. But I mean, there are also biological reasons for why people are transphobic, or why people identify as cats, or why people murder other people, so that's not a good argument anyway! It's just appeal to nature!  An actually good argument is a psychological one. I, as a trans man, have vastly improved wellbeing post-transition, and that is also scientifically verifiable. Like you can actually do studies and show that when trans people transition, they become much healthier and happier. And that should be enough! If there were studies showing that 'cat people' have higher wellbeing when they are referred to as cats... I'd refer to them as cats! The biological basis doesn't matter, and it won't matter till we find markers so precise that we could actually make diagnostic tests out of them. Till then, the best explanation I have for why I am a man despite not living as one for most of my life is 'it feels right'. And really, does any cis man have a better one? Doubt it. So that's why it is enough for me.

The three-way debate and how it had me rolling with laughter reminded me of Mr Bennett in Pride and Prejudice: 'For what do we live, but to make sport for our neighbours, and laugh at them in our turn?' I doubt theory is going to help us dissolve this divide. I suspect it is going to take something more akin to grace and good humour.

My grandma used to say, 'It takes all kinds,' whenever she'd see interesting folks out in the real world. She never put too much thought into the hows or the whys, and instead worked to make that person feel welcome and comfortable when engaging them, or providing quiet empathy and acceptance otherwise. 'It takes all kinds of fruits to make a fruit salad.'  I kinda get peoples' need to categorize and order and label everything, and put things into neat and tidy little boxes. Helps to cut back on panic and surprises. Helps to set expectations accordingly. People love shortcuts. But at the end of the day it doesn't really matter who fits where according to whatever definitions are being spun up this time around. There's no need to make bullshit over-complicated. Be happy to be part of the salad. Be thankful for the experience, and try to make the experience better not just for yourself but for those around you too. We're here only for a limited amount of time. Maybe we shouldn't piss all over it?  I'm about as cishet as it gets. That cement has dried long ago. The ten missing arguments (sorry for the long post):   1. Transmedicalism creates the justification for HRT and gender reassignment surgery.   2. Transmedicalism as a mental disorder creates pathways for research funding from large organizations, particularly for treatment.   3. The trans community needs political support to assist with getting rights like protection against workplace discrimination. Scientific explanations create support from political parties that value science and rationalism.   4. If you don't care about surgeries, research funding, or legal protections, then yes, abandoning transmedicalism seems like a completely valid position.   5. Nonbinary people don't have to call themselves trans. To do so seems an explicitly political decision, and thus, should be criticized for its political value.   6. Circus members often were societally mistreated for biological qualities such as unusual hairgrowth, being conjoined twins, albinism, dwarfism, extreme size, age, amputations, mircocephaly, or just being an unusual race or born into a foreign culture. A woman who naturally grows a beard probably shouldn't be placed into the same category as someone who chooses to put on a beard -- although even that statement feels fraught.   7. Baltimore also attempted to self-righteously bully and condescend Tiffany, and also used strong-arm tactics to try to get the moderator on their side. Yet, Baltimore's bullying tactics go unaddressed. Only Tiffany is expected to be accepting and magnanimous.   8. Mental health diagnoses have heavy psychological and performative elements. For example, performatively, major depression requires significant distress or impairment in social, occupational, or other functioning. Psychologically, suicidal ideation may happen entirely in the mind, but its presence in a patient sets off alarm bells. A brain scan may help scientists understand depression, but it's not required to make a diagnosis -- nor to prescribe very biological medicine to assist. However, this does not make depression unbacked by medical science; current research shows its connections to genetic factors and physical factors such as diet, exercise, and particularly, sunlight. However, Baltimore's criticism of Tiffany not having brain scans for her diagnosis would seem to criticize the reality of all mental disorders, especially ones only recognized in the present day. Justine and Baltimore both rely on appeals to ignorance, and Tiffany is helpless to respond, because she's not an expert on mental health or research into gender dysphoria specifically.   9. On the same issue, people who suffer from depression are often told that it's a choice to be depressed. This is often used in a cruelly dismissive or condescending way that can cause deep emotional anguish. Baltimore uses the same tactic on Tiffany, which seems as outright insulting and cruel as misgendering someone. That doesn't excuse Tiffany's own misgendering and cruelty, but no one addresses Baltimore's viciousness.   10. Yes, it's an artistic video. So maybe some of these absences are purposeful. But the general theme of anti-science, anti-medicine, and anti-political-reality seem very... off-brand. Also, I don't think a lot of the painful aspects of having someone question a mental health diagnosis were intended. The content warnings include transphobia and racism, but not mental illness and ableism, even though the process of talking to therapists and doctors comes up explicitly in the video.

I guess the only definition of a 'transtrender' is someone who starts or stops being 'trans' because they think it's either in or out of fashion or convenient/inconvenient instead of because they've come to the actual conclusion that they are or aren't trans.  The problem with the 'transtrender' situation is that nobody but the suspected 'transtrender' themself can actually say if they were one or not.  If they really believed they were another gender at the time then decided they weren't later, they were never a 'transtrender', they were just figuring things out.  If they reveal that they decided to be another gender based only on 1.) something superficial/surface level such as labels or looks, 2.) a whim, or 3.) not at all about if this is who they really are or if they actually felt like they were that gender, they were probably a 'transtrender' at that time.  However, none of these thoughts or feelings can be confirmed by anyone other than the person who you think might be a 'transtrender'.   Basically, you can only say someone's a 'transtrender' if the actual person reveals it themself later on. If you accuse someone of being one when they haven't openly admitted they were then you're more than likely shitting on someone for just trying to figure themself out over a period of time, which is perfectly normal.

I think there is a valid point to be made that we do not know exactly why being transgender is valid, but that it does not change the fact that it is. The effect of transitioning can be easily measured and isn't explained by any theory that denies this. As recently as that genderdysforia was recognised as thing, this year the world health organisation removed it from the list of mental disorders. I hope this changes the way my country approaches transgender treatment. At the moment there is an 18 month waiting list, before you see a psychiatrist for over a year, where he then decides if you get treatment, through a truly ghoulish protocol.  I think it not being seen as a mental disorder is a good thing, seeing it that way actually invalidates people, like treatment indulges in some kind of delusion.  Interestingly, there are a whole bunch of species of animal that have the physical capacity to change their own gender, chromosomes be damned. As most species have some kind of common ancestry if you look back far enough, I think a case can be made that the desire or need to transition, or not conform, can actually be perfectly natural.  We don't need to prove that we are who we are, that as a fact, can simply be observed.

I do think there is a variant of trans medicalism that is less difficult - 'transition as treatment' - where the focus is on the empirical results of improved mood, reduced suicide rates, etc etc in people who have undergone various forms of transition. As sciencey as antidepressants (perhaps more so, given the woeful trial performance of many psychiatric drugs), very easy to explain, quite hard to argue against. ContraPoints makes some great videos, and with that being said, there were some points in this video that sounded great, but don't make sense when you break down her points.

When it comes to the fact that people with gender dysphoria (generally) don't have brain scans to 'prove' their ttransgenderism, well, why would this matter?  Mental illness in general is diagnosed by a doctor asking the patient questions and then basing their diagnosis off of that.  For any other mental illness, a brain scan wouldn't be necessary to show that their mental disorder is legitimate. Natalie pointing out that Tiffany Tumbles doesn't have a brain scan felt like a point well made, but that same view point mapped onto any other mental illness wouldn't make sense. The lack of a brain scan doesn't pull the rug out from under a transmedicalist point of view at all, it is just inconsistent from a scientifically accurate view of mental illness.

Personally, I think that trans people are defined by having gender dysphoria.  Of course, I also support people having a gender-nonconforming presentation, I just don't think it makes sense to call that being transgender.  The beneficial thing about this point of view is that it accurately identifies people with gender dysphoria from a medical stance, and also allows for support of people exploring their gender identity.  Just because gender dysphoria is necessary to be a transgender person in no way prevents a healthy exploration of gender.  It just means that until a person is confirmed to have gender dysphoria, their presentation and such falls only under the category of gender expression. With these distinctions, people who are exploring their identity can do so in a healthy way until they reach a point where they can recognize if they are cis or trans.

The part of the video that bothered me the most was at 21:52, because Natalie subtly changes how she is defining a transmedicalist view point.  Instead of saying that a person needs gender dysphoria to be transgender, she is saying defines it as a person needing to medically transition.  The distinction between requiring a person to experience gender dysphoria and requiring a person to medically transition will make or break the transmedicalist view point and I think that it is intellectually dishonest for her to disregard this distinction.

At 23:45 Natalie presents a false dichotomy by saying that, 'gender is either psychological, or biological, or social'.  She presents the cause of gender as being only *one* of these three things, when that's not necessarily true at all.  When she gets to the biological POV, she says it only works if you use a wrong brain in the wrong body argument and state that she doesn't buy that.  I wish Natalie would have been less dismissive of this point of view because I think it has a lot more nuance that she gave it credit for. As we can see through the existence of intersex people, female sex features can naturally occur in men and vise versa.  We have no reason to think that brains should be any different from reproductive organs. The fact is, there are distinct differences in cis male and cis female brains.  Based on the science that is currently available, trans people have significant deviations in their brain structure from what is typical for their biological sex, even before medically transitioning.  Does every sex different feature of the brain show atypical features in trans people? No. But the fact that there are significant differences pretransition indicates that it is scientifically dishonest to write off the brain/body swap theory. There is A LOT of nuance involved in how our brains work and make us do and think what we do. Clearly, there is a lot more that needs to be researched, and there is definitely not enough evidence to justify thinking that this theory has been made up for gate-keeping.

On non-binary people: A biological explanation of transgenderism doesn't undercut the very real existence of non-binary people. Remember that nuance in our brains I mentioned? Well here is where that becomes even more relevant than before. If every last sex different feature of our brains isn't 'flipped' in trans people, then how much needs to be 'flipped' for a person to turn out to be the gender opposite what their genitals would imply? The gradient between male and female is where non-binary people exist.

So this transmedicalist point of view doesn't alienate non-binary people by default.  The transmedicalist people who do think that non-binary people aren't valid are being problematic from in a way separate from the transmedicalist view.

Phew, trying to collect my thoughts here. First of all, this was a great video. Lots of good points here all around made by all the characters. Now, for what i think.  Well, what is said on the 2nd part of the video is true, you can't exactly prove trans are 'real'. To me, it's because... they're not. Let me clarify. Why do people identify as trans? Because they identify with some of the things that are usually attributed to the other sex in the cliches1. Saying you're trans because you have interests relating to the other sex's cliches seems to imply that sexes are confined to the cliches; which isn't true at all, there's a lot of diversity on both sides! Basically, i am making the argument that genders simply don't exist. Everyone simply has different ways of being, and should do how they please without putting names on it.  Now, i think i know why people do that. They simply are scared to be shamed by other people for not acting like they should. Simple answer? 'I'm not a man/woman'. It's an easy way of getting out of the situation, but it is simply genetically not true. Instead, you should simply own your likes and passions without putting them on a sort of scapegoat. It's the same situation with non-binary really, if you want to act cat-like, well, you can. It doesn't make you a real cat though. Reality... exists. I really can't put this any other way; as much as we sometimes wish we were something else physically, we aren't.  Also, about gender dysphoria: on that point i agree with the 'Baltimore' character (6:23): if you're convinced you're a 'real' trans with real problems, you're eventually going to convince a psychiatrist. Because, it's no rocket science: the psychiatrist subtly asks you what you think is true, until you convince him (and maybe yourself) of it. Then, if other people experience the same phenomenon, a name is put on it as a generalization. I'd say the feelings people are experiencing are due to social pressure explained earlier2.  So, these feelings would be kind of a shield people use to explain to other people their quirky interests, in a time where more and more people are bullied online. See twitter. Sorry to be blunt but twitter is a real cesspool, people are asked to explain themselves all the time, forcing them to adopt a defensive stance. This, and the fact that internet popularized trans-identity, leads to more and more people finding and hiding behind the 'trans shield'; hence why it ended up becoming a recognized condition (dysphoria). So, with that theory in mind, what was diagnosed as problems with gender identity might just be a symptom of the mental protection against bullying.   1(You could make the argument that the cliches are linked to the genders themselves instead of the sex, but that would be dishonest. The origin of the cliches are based on the sex; like how the blue toy isle aimed marketing at the sexually male children, and not male-gendered children.)  2(In reference to paragraph 2)  If you think i have missed something, or disagree, feel free to respond, i'll gladly have a chat with you guys ^^  P.S.: This doesn't mean you can't call yourself a girl if you want to, nothing wrong with that! But please, don't annoy anyone with your interests and/or kinks! Also remember: a 'gender' isn't a personality; i see so many furry friends fall in the trap of limiting their personality to the 'basic furry', it's pretty sad really. Being yourself is the key to stand out, don't become conformist to any standard, even a different standard than 'normie' standard!  P.P.S.: Ok i've been writing this for 1h15. Time to resolve myself to let go of this. Oh well. It won't ever be perfect anyways.

My philosophy of gender is that gender is neither ideological, biological nor social. Gender is associative. One does not necessarily identify as a gender but more accurately identifies WITH a gender. Though a combination of conscious and unconscious, subtle and direct, social, ideological and biological factors, one builds a personal construct of gender. This construct of gender is re-enforced through association. In a very rough example one may go through life seeing long hair, pink, their mother and high heels and associate them with the label female, and by extension each other.  You can break down the layers of association into four groups: Social-Conscious, Social-Unconscious, Individual-Conscious and Individual-Unconscious. Social as in directed outward and individual as in directed inward. When one's Individual-Unconscious association of a particular classification of gender (i.e. maleness, femaleness etc.) matches with their classification of themselves, that is what we call gender identity.  The categories are formed and changed through association. The easiest category of association to influence is the Social-Conscious and the hardest one is the Individual-Unconscious. I do believe that the Individual-Unconscious theoretically can be changed, but to try to do so would be akin to trying to ungrow a tree or unshatter a glass, it is nearly impossible and is more trouble than it's worth.  In this model trans bigotry can be explained by someone's Social-Concious misaligning with a trans person's Individual-Unconscious and Trans disphoria is explained by one's Social-Unconscious misaligning with their Individual-Unconscious.  Feel free to pick apart my theory. Thank you for listening to my Tedtalk. I'll be accepting my Nobel prize in Gender Studies now.

I love Justine's breakdown of gender as either biological, psychological, or sociological, but I think that rather than having to pick one of those things to be 'the real thing', ALL THREE OF THEM are real things, and we need language to differentiate between them. We already have the word 'sex' to be clear when we mean 'biological gender', so that's handled. The sociological sense of the word 'gender' is the one with historical priority, so I also agree with Justine that that's the right referent of the word 'gender' simpliciter.  But Justine's account of gender as a psychological property is missing a lot. 'Just identifying' is itself a sociological thing, not a psychological thing, so that's not something we really need to address beyond sociological gender. But 'gender' dysphoria and euphoria are genuine psychological things: they're how you psychologically feel about the biological sex of your body. And I've been saying for a while now that we need a third word to identify that property of a person, separate from sex ('biological gender') and gender ('sociological gender').  I've suggested the word 'bearing' for that property, because the root '-phor' means 'to bear', and 'bearing' makes a nice navigational metaphor together with 'orientation': your orientation is where you're facing (i.e. who you're looking at), while your bearing is where you're heading (i.e. who you aim to become).

Post-Modernism, due to its nature seems like a permamnent dead end. The entire foundations of social constructions are being undermined: scientific truth, gender, sexuality, art, etc.; and since the foundation is destroyed, there is nothing to built upon anymore.   You can imagine a leap from modernism to post-modernism for example - there is a clear sense of progression: people quiestioned the order of things, their valididty, hence post-modernism was born. You can imagine a person from the 19th century thinking up what the next step of social evolution would be like. But the situation  with post-modernism is different: nothing can be built when the construction blocks are destroyed.   So, I thought that maybe thats it, the end of history. In 200 years we are still gonna be stuck in post-modernism. The meta-modernism is bullshit. The definition of 'mediations between aspects of both modernism and postmodernism' is vague and inapplicable, its indistinguishable from post-modernism. The New Sincerity is bullshit. It lacks substance to be called an entirely new movement. Its either reactionary, when people really don't like the post-modernism paradigm, so they just return to the modernist ways, or, its, again, post-modern, a way to subvert expectations when they have already been subverted. This is not the same as positive realism, where the things exist the way we feel they do. This is 'things exist, and the reason for their existance does not have to be proved by logic. They exist because they do.'  This does sound dellusional, this does sound irrational, anywhere, anytime you would have said this, people would disagree. We always have to prove the theory with rational thinking. It only feels logical:  - So you are saying trans people are not schizophrenic, why? - Well, because of reason number one, reason number two and the causational link between them. - Okay, I agree.  What you are saying is that we don't have to do this, not because we just want this thing to be true really badly, but because this thing really does exist, and the proof is our feelings.   You are spearheading an onslaught onto the entire method of rational thinking, not in the post-modern, 'dismantle everything way', but in a constructive way. You are replacing rationality with something that has yet to be given name to. And if this is true, then you are in fact, one of the prominent philosophers of our time.  Must feel quite annoyed that that philosophy degree turned out to be the thing you will ultimately be categorized by.\\\\\\

I feel like this video misrepresents non-binary people to some extent. Not all non-binary people are androgynous. Many are. Just as many women are feminine and many men are masculine. But very feminine afab nonbinary people exist and very masculine amab nonbinary people exist. They still know their gender identity.  Connections to neurological development exist if you need that connection; eg, people with conditions relating to androgynous neurological development, such as autistic people and people with hormone conditions that have impacted them since they were in the womb or during early childhood, are statistically more likely to experience queer identities (though these experiences obviously don't always overlap). The connection to neurological development just isn't always clear. We wouldn't even know where to look to find it on a brain scan. Why do we need to see it on a brain scan for something to be there in the brain? They can't spot sexuality on brain scans but I think it's still reflected in our brains somewhere. In my opinion, gender is biological, psychological, and social. Gender identity is the result of multiple complex and intertwined factors.   At the end of the day, it does all come down to how a person feels and identifies. Facts don't care about your feelings unless the facts being discussed are your feelings. If I say 'I feel sad' people can turn around and tell me 'you're faking it. You seem pretty happy to me. Things are going well for you and you're so privileged in so many ways that of course you're happy. You're just lying about being sad for attention.' That would be a strange reaction and wouldn't actually mean I'm not sad. Maybe I'm not and am lying for attention, I suppose, but at the end of the day I'm the only one with access to my mind and the ability to know what I'm feeling. No amount of brain scans will inform anyone else better than I on what I feel. Whether it be emotions or gender identity.

this is a complicated subject. i disagree with your contention that 'identity' is something arbitrary, that anyone can choose to be man, woman.. cat, dog, etc. there is a biological basis for identity. it's rooted in the brain, somehow. and perhaps other parts of the body as well. my point is, there is a plausible explanation for why transsexuals exist. perhaps due to some hormonal imbalance in the uterus before the baby is born, as you mentioned in the video. there have also been trans people throughout history, in whatever form.. hijra, two spirit. this biological basis for identity manifests itself in a psychology that sees itself as man or woman, or perhaps non-binary. people used to think (and some still do) that people who think this way are deluded. however we can provide them with a scientific basis for transsexualism, as well as its existence throughout human history and in all cultures, as evidence this is not a delusion. if some people identity themselves as a cat or a dog, there does not seem to be much biological basis for this. other than perhaps the person really is deluded. or it may just be a form of cultural role-playing. i agree what makes someone a man or woman is not the clothes they wear, the roles they occupy in society, their mannerisms, the way they talk. to me, these are superficial things, subject to culture. imo what makes someone a man or woman is self-knowledge. this is an innate sense. it really does not need explanation or justification (partly because i don't think an adequate explanation can be provided). this self-knowledge, in a transsexual, is manifested as a desire to be a man or woman. this is an incredibly strong desire, and one that can never be quenched. this desire may not make one a man or woman. but it surely points out one is a transsexual, or transgender. this desire is as strong (if nor more) than the desire one experiences for sex (for people who are sexual). the question whether a trans woman is a woman, and vice-versa, seems to be a different question. this has more to do with societal acceptance of transsexuals or trans people, and how society wants to integrate us into its social fabric, instead of seeing us as 'freaks' (simply because we cannot be understood, we are so strange to them, abnormal) this secondary question about a trans persons womanhood or manhood does not nullify the existence of trans people, which can be shown to have a biological basis (and therefore valid in a scientific factual sense). i don't know how society will integrate trans people, if it even happens. at the moment, existent categories of man, woman seem to be the only options available in how they can regard us. perhaps new gender categories could be created to accomodate us. anyway, being trans is rooted in biology, even if we don't understand the exact mechanics. this seems to be a more reasonable explanation than saying it's simply something that is arbitrarily chosen, based on cultural preferences. identity as man or woman in a trans person is based on self-knowledge (which does not need explanation) this identity (self-knowledge) is manifested as a strong unquenchable desire to be a man or a woman. imo this is what i see as the fundamental aspect of transsexualism: desire. a trans woman desires to be a woman, and vice-versa.

Regrettably, transmedicalism is a complete misreading of psychological science. Psychiatric disorders are identified by their symptoms *and only* by their symptoms. In a very real sense, they are the symptoms. Gender dysphoria cannot prove the existence of an underlying transness because it is only itself. Even if a true biological transness that weren't simply interdefinable with the brain structures responsible for causing dysphoria existed, by virtue of the fact that dysphoria *is not that,* dysphoria cannot prove its presence.  Now, say dysphoria weren't interdefinable with the underlying trans factor (whatever it is); what's that factor? Literally, what is it? What could it possibly be? Why isn't it psychologically diagnosible? Why can't a patient attest to having it in the same way they attest to dysphoria? Why can't it be demonstrated by otherwise examining the patient or their life in the normal way one evaluates psychological disorders?  We've already established asymptomatic psychological disorders aren't things though.

interestingly Baltimore never denies experiencing dysphoria, it's only other people who claim they do. I'm NB myself and dysphoria was a topic so mired in concepts about what genitalia you did or didn't have that conversations outside of it (shapes, sounds, how you are perceived, how androgyny is discussed or typically represented) got completely buried. Enough that for a long time I thought because I didn't have /this/ particular brand of dysphoria, I must not have it at all. NVM bottom dysphoria is just one part of the total experience for trans folks, one that's exceptionally complex when you live somewhere between the normative ends of the gender spectrum. So dysphoria is experienced, but with different factors that is shared in common between NB people and trans on the whole than trans folks who navigate to the far ends of the spectrum.
