This was both really satisfying to see and also really exhausting. I used to BE that person, who said you could only be trans if you had dysphoria. I used to identify as a cis girl for it, because I thought 'yeah I don't really CARE about pronouns, I dont see why I have to feeeeel like a girl, dunno what that means, but I dont have dysphoria!'   It took a long, long time to feel okay with using the word trans on myself, despite finally admitting I was nonbinary a couple years ago, mostly because I felt like people would be angry if I called myself trans. I felt like I basically didn't exist by any of society's standards or the queer community's standards--I'm an aroace nobinary, who also happens to be Middle Eastern so is forced to identify as white. How exhausting is that? To feel wrong on every level because nobody will be cool with what you are?  But yeah, it's nothing wrong with me. It's what's wrong with a system desperate to box people in for profit and prejudice. Gender is this mix of societal and personal, simply because society is so broken that people who are binary trans feel that if they slack for even a SECOND, they will be invalidated. And most trans people in general have depression! They can't be expected to give it their all every second of every day! That's really not fair to them, to say that because they aren't conforming to society's concept of their gender, it can be called into question.   Hell, some days they might actually like the way they are presenting for a whole minute. It's like the dysphoria isn't even that big a deal. Do they stop being trans? No? What? Listen, all dysphoria is, is having a mental map of your body that the physical form doesn't match, and feeling pretty understandably upset at that disconnect. Who is expected to map out their mental image of themself for the sake of science? Nobody! In the same way depression is based off symptoms and not brain scans, and medication becomes a guessing game as they try to narrow down what is causing the feeling (seratonin not being produced? not being absorbed? being absorbed too fast? all different! all depression.)   It took so long for me to recognize that, yeah, I don't like being called a girl. I don't like having breasts, and I want to be this weird middle ground that people can't tell at a glance. I did not feel comfortable experimenting with gender because I thought other people experimenting (in extreme ways) were weird.   What is wrong with testing extremes so we can find a middle ground, anyway? If it's a 'trend', it's a trend only in the sense that, for a little while, someone identifies as some wild random thing just out of desperation to not be 'boy' or 'girl'. Oh no! A lot of people testing nonbinary waters in crazy ways! Whatever shall we do!! I know! Let's call them crazy for considering any sense of nonbinary-ness to begin with! And at the end of the day, all I hear is 'nonbinary isn't a thing.'   Listen, gender is a gradient of a spectrum. People are constantly in flux every day on other scales, and it's okay for them to be flux in terms of how they view and present themselves as well.    God, I'm sorry. This got long, and will probably disappear into the mass of comments on this video. It just hit hard for me, and I got kind of scared to watch your videos when YT first started recommending me, because I expected belittlement. I'm so used to not being taken seriously in terms of gender and sexuality, this year's pride month was the first time I didn't feel like an outlier. It feels really, really nice, in a sort of bittersweet way, to have someone take this thing so seriously, from all sides, desperately trying to show that yes, this is a complex topic, but empathy and understanding is so important, and gatekeeping hurts people instead of helping.   So. Thanks.

It seems rather apparent to me that gender isn't exclusively sociological, psychological or biological. Any conceptualization of gender is necessarily socially constructed in the context of the society we live in, hence an essential biological 'maleness' or 'femaleness' is impossible. However there undeniably are underlying biological factors that drive extremely strong feelings that coincide with the social construct of gender, only it does not map perfectly and so we make adjustments to the concepts we think in for the sake of our own sanity and ask society to humor us, so that we may not feel like absolute shit all the time. I think that's basically all there is to it and with that understanding in mind it should be obvious that you shouldn't bother transitioning to some social ideal, but to whatever makes you feel happy and comfortable.

It seems to me that there's something fundamentally wrong about Tiffany's enterprise. No one should have to justify their inner truth or their right to exist as they truly are. We should make this socially unacceptable whenever dismissal happens. Are you a wolfkin? Cool. Do you sincerely identify as an attack helicopter (e.g. are you working for the day when you can upload your consciousness into a machine mind who's body is an attack helicopter)? You're fuckin' valid. 100% valid, full stop. So what about people like rachel dolezal? There may not be a single answer, but I have to think that we should lean towards acceptance unless there are seriously bad consequences to such acceptance. Even then there may be ways of mitigating those consequences while still accepting the deviant. Accepting the deviant should be the default. It should feel extremely wrong to not accept the deviant, no matter how much they deviate. What about people who are lying or taking the piss? Fuck 'em. Unless/until they reveal themselves, life's too short to worry about those assholes. This is definitely a strong opinion loosely held, I still need to think more about this, but my gut tells me that policing who is and isn't valid for the sake of placating elements of society that are hostile to your existence is a really really bad idea that ultimately will do much more harm than good.

From a systemic view, you would notice that several things can affect brain development over the period of a person's life. That's biological hormonal differences that arise because of hard differences between the sexes (gonads) and the societal influences which arise from both biology and from sociology.  These all interact with each other to shape brains, bone, appearances, everything. But that the human body is so malleable gives hope to change.  I don't like that there is some worry that innateness will be an excuse or is used as a reasoning to 'not do something'. That seems more of a problem with the person who uses the innateness of their biology or blames things as being unchangeable than it has to do with the underlying facts of biology. The more we learn of the human body, the more we learn just how much it can be changed and how little even bones are set.

Have you considered the argument from Evolutionary Psychology?  (Let's see what I can do in a YouTube comment to describe it)  First, evolutionary psych is the theory that some of our psychological traits were naturally selected for their fitness. Like physical traits, you wouldn't expect every fit trait to show up in every individual, but fit traits would show up in most individuals. Rough (real rough) example: the ability for parents (and especially mothers) to bond strongly w/their offspring is a fit trait that is commonly found in the population.  The goal of evolutionary psych is to explain how and why many human behaviors seem to be so widespread regardless of cultural context.  Ok, w/that brief explanation that doesn't do it justice, let's jump over to personality trait theory: the theory that there are (at minimum) 5 fundamental traits that, when mixed and matched, make up personalities. Ex: openess to expierence. A person who has this trait will seek out new experiences and a person who doesn't, won't. Except it's not actually a binary but a spectrum, so someone would be placed somewhere between completely open and completely closed.  There are 5 traits that have a buttload of proof, and the research psych community is testing 2 others, so the end result might be 7. The point is though, that each person's personality can be desrcibed using these traits. Imagine you had a panel with 5 sliders in front of you. Everyone has the same 5 sliders, but each of us has a slightly different configuration. The important piece to take away from this theory is that the sliders are set. We are born with our personalities, and once we reach adulthood, they remain stable throughout the rest of our lives. Finally, we inherit these traits (our personality sliders will be some combination of our parents), thereby showinng that psychological traits can be passed down and can be inherit, though our actual behaviors will be a product of our personality reacting to our context.  So, what does any of that have to do with trans people and gender? Well, when combined, I think they provide the most compelling/explanatory theory of gender.  Gender is not a social construct (a pox on performative theory!), it's a bundle of psychological traits similar to personality. Who knows how many traits make up a gender (4, 5, 6? Let's do research to find out!) but combined, you get a person's gender, a stable psychological identity that influences a person's behavior.  But why did we evolve genders, and why do they seem so intertwined with sex? Well, b/c they're useful. It is useful for ppl with penises/uteruses to have some preloaded behaviors that help them make the best use of that equipement. And because genders are an evolved feature, you would expect most people to have the most fit (for producing children) combination of gender and sex, which is what we see. Most people are straight and cis (oh yeah, sexuality got thrown in under this theory as a trait making up the gender profile). But also because it's an evolved trait, you would not expect every individual to have the most fit (for producing children, not at life in general, do not use this to bash queer ppl!) combination because shit happens and the real world is messy like that, cue the entire lgbtq spectrum.  'But gender presentation is so culturally bound!' I can hear the performative theorists screaming.  Well, that's why I make a distinction between gender and gender roles. Gender is inherit to an individual, gender roles are constructions of society. Here's how they interact using an anolgy between a sex characteristic and a gender role:  As a transman, I noticed a legit lessening of my tendency to express strong emotions (sadness, anger, pride) via tears when I had high testosterone levels. I definately feel as though it is necessary for there to be a space for nonbinary people in the trans community. The 'trans enough' debate reminds me a lot of the 'lesbian enough' debate, where there are 'gold star' lesbians and spaces exist where lesbians refuse to date women who have dated men. Strait people often invalidated the experiences of wlw by asserting that it is 'just a phase' or that it stems from trauma, and no doubt this was damaging. So people clung to sexual orientation being solely genetic and set in stone in order to defend themselves, such that it invalidated the experiences for women of whom those things were true. Maybe some woman legitamently did have trauma that made it impossible for her to feel comfortble in a relationship with a man, but if she were honest about it, she would likely be rejected by the lesbian community for not being lesbian enough. But the way I see it, this woman only dates women now, and so she's lesbian enough, no matter how she may have identified in the past or what the 'cause' is.  I think everyone in the queer community has at some point been guilty of looking at someone and thinking 'they aren't queer enough,' because we are afraid of how strait or cis people might use these people as evidence to invalidate our own experiences. And so we fall back on imposing the same limitations that are set on us. We give rules so only those who are 'queer enough' are let in, and more and more we impose strait/cis ideas of normalcy. 'I'm trans enough because I have dysphoria and can pass.' 'I'm gay enough because I have never questioned my orientation.' 'I'm bi enough because I like all genders exactly equally.' In an attempt to make LGBTQ lives 'normal,' we've set standards of normalcy to meet and turned the lives of queer people into chess pieces to move our agenda of 'Look! Queer people are normal just like strait and cis people!' when what we should be doing is dismantaling our dependance on normalcy and let people take ownership of their own lives, the same way we want to take ownership of our own.

I'm cis, but damn, I've felt that 'am I just a trender because I haven't felt X' as an ace person. When I started questioning and researching asexuality, a lot of ace people said that they had felt broken, or that something was wrong with them. I had never felt that. At most I thought 'oh maybe I'm just late or something' as a 17-year old who had never masturbated, let alone kissed someone.   I mean, I'm so grateful that I didn't have to struggle with feeling broken on top of my general lack of selfconfidence, but it also led to doubts of 'am I really ace? Do I really belong in the LGBTQ+ community? Am I a fraud for walking in the pride parade?' until I had my first (and thus far only) sexual experience. If that night was a test, I totally aced it (badum tss).   I might edit or add to this section after a rewatch, but the part of 'performing gender' and if a man playing a woman for 2 hours /makes/ him a woman for those hours immediately got me thinking of Takarazuka.   Short intro: Takarazuka is a Japanese theatre company that only employs women in all roles. It was founded in 1914 and is actually a school with two years of classes. The first year all girls train together but in the second year they choose/gets chosen whether they want to specialise in female roles (musumeyaku) or male roles (otokoyaku). If a student becomes a otokoyaku she cuts her hair short, starts using masculine pronouns, is taught how to behave more 'manly' and is only allowed to wear traditionally masculine clothes aka RIP all skirts.   Okay intro over, the thing I got thinking about is that the otokoyaku ladies are low-key performing a masculine gender always, as long as they're with the company. I guess you could call their stage time as high-key performing, because then they're seen not as women-playing-men, but as 'actual' men. Mostly because the company is big on the 'no homo' thing after two big scandals of fans sending real love letters to the performers and a lesbian couple was found out within the company. I think both scandals was around the 30's but I'm tangeting.   The thing I meant to get to was a quote from the wikipedia page about Zuka. It's from two former otokoyaku actresses and (to me at least) shows two different spectres of performing gender.   'Tsurugi Miyuki, top otokoyaku star [top star = leader, gets all main roles] of the Moon troupe, said that she conceived male impersonation as just a 'role' that she wore like the makeup and costume that helped create her otokoyaku image. She said that she reverts to her nonperforming 'feminine' self after performance. Other otokoyaku feel uncomfortable switching to female roles. Otokoyaku Matsu Akira, who retired in 1982, stated: 'Even though I am a female, the thing called 'female' just won't emerge at all.'

I'm genuinely a transmed myself and I disagree with policing presentation and dysphoria. There's no goddamn reason to tell NB or GNC transsexuals they're 'invalid' because their dysphoria isn't ours to dictate. Only their doctor can dispute their dysphoria, and it's not fair to call GNC trans people 'non-dysphoric'. It's pretty straight-forward, and I can't believe how many people still think all dysphoria is body dysphoria. Social dysphoria exists and is acknowledged medically. Wanting to be called different pronouns and a different name to what you're assigned? That's also part of dysphoria! Wanting to transition at all, is part of dysphoria. All forms of transition are valid forms. It doesn't just have to be medical. Transition is just a journey to living in a way that you're more comfortable with. I've been trying to rally transmeds together and spread these ideas. I don't like the misconception that dysphoria is self hate when all it is is the desire to transition to a different gender experience. This includes NB identities too. That's genuinely how most doctors see it, as well.

Huh. Well that's a lot to think about. I don't think everyone's needs can be met at once. I'm a trans med centrist trash trans guy, (I do think Dave Rubin is a hack, lmao) and while I think there are still arguments for favoring transmedicalism that are motivated by reasons more legitimate and not selfish and shitty [see 'self loathing bully'], you offer so much more than anyone else I've ever heard on the 'sjw' side of the argument, and damn it I wish we could talk.  Medical transition is extremely important for some people (it's improved my life dramatically), and I don't think informed consent is gonna cut it, especially if we need to solve the very real problem of figuring out how to respond to dysphoria in kids, and navigating the complicated causes for desire to medically transition, and that mental health professionals may be inadvertently offering people treatments that do more harm than good, if the person's dysphoria is rooted in trauma or sexism or internalized homophobia, etc. - in short, I don't think we can ignore the need to better determine who will and won't be helped by medical transition. Without attempting to develop some kind of theory around how all this shit works, how do we address this? I don't think pure informed consent is good enough, and while preventing needed transition is obviously a real problem, so is poorly addressing what may be other mental health issues. Does that necessarily turn in to scrutinizing peoples' identities? Is that worse? What creates a better outcome? Can we get by with 'no theory'?

I know I'm dating myself with this, but back in the day when we didn't use the term 'social media' but instead we had a 'blogosphere,' there was a community question posed at Feministing (told you I was dating myself) that really stuck with me and has ever since: What makes you feel like your gender identity?

And it stuck with me because I didn't know how to answer it. I'm a cis woman and I have trouble imagining myself any other way. And not for lack of trying: I've done a lot of internal interrogation of my feelings and my womanhood and ~what it all means to me~ (mostly because it just seems like a good idea to take inventory of that sort of thing), and I never come away with anything other than 'woman.' I just don't have any good reason for it. I love playing with androgyny in my aesthetic expression, and transgressing strictly defined gender roles, and there's plenty of experiences or realities attached to the idea of 'womanhood' that I would gladly throw in the trash at the first given opportunity.

At the end of the day, I'm a woman because I just am. There's no logic or reason to it, it's just A Thing That Is True About Me. I lucked out both by having one of the Two Officially Accepted Binary Genders, and by having the genitals that are assumed to go with it, so nobody questions it. Which is what you hit on in this video: There's no rationalization or reason for any of this, it all comes down to some weird nebulous ~feeling~ that you can't explain, but that you know is true. I feel like there's something that I'm not understanding. Why do we have to view dysphoria through a purely biological understanding of the trans experience? Is dysphoria incompatible with a performative theory of gender? I recognize that it's a cisnormative framing, but there must be some sort of negative emotion associated with embodying the social role of someone's assigned gender that would cause them to choose to identify themselves as nonbinary.* As I said before I may simply be understanding the true definition of dysphoria.   I also can't help but feel the video glosses over the intricacies of childhood transition. From my personal experience with being 'a trender' the issues of transmedicalism and the place of dysphoria in the trans experience weren't really relevant. Adolescence is generally a time of self hatred and dissatisfaction. Therefore the issue is not the question of dysphoria's relevance but its misidentification. It can be very comforting to explain away a complex dissatisfaction with oneself through adopting the trans identity, whether or not it is fitting. Obviously this discussion is tangential to the main topic of the video, but it seems it should have been left out if it weren't going to be discussed in depth.  Finally, I'd just like to have a more nuanced understanding of the non-binary communities relationship with social categorization. Baltimore Maryland says many times that they don't want to be beholden to societal groupings. This, to me, seems to be antithetical to the trend towards increasing specificity in the labeling of gender and sexual identifies. While I understand the stated goal of these labels is to create a sense of acceptance, it's hard to shake the feeling that at a point they shift from fostering community to being banners behind which to rally in the 'oppression olympics'. If the idea of gender noncomformity is based partially on the idea that the distinction of gender is inherently oppressive, then isn't hyper-categorizing of these identities counter-productive. I understand that this argument does fall into the trap the Natalie talked about in her last video (trans people shouldn't exist because abolish gender), but I still feel like it has some place in the conversation about the validity of certain people's identities.   *obviously in a society without preexisting expectations of gender the question of dysphoria wouldn't be an issue, but with the inevitability of some level of oppression in the world today there must be some personal reason for transition   (ie avoidance of dysphoria) that makes enduring that oppression 'worth it'  Thank you to anyone that had the patience to make it through this mess!

Hey transmed truscum transwoman here, I feel like I'd like to actually rationalize my beliefs because I don't think Tiffany did a good job at it.   First my beliefs, I believe gender dysphoria is a medically diagnosable condition that essentially means the person diagnosed has discomfort with their gender assigned at birth. I don't believe that definition excludes non binary people or identities I also don't believe that someone needs to transition if they have gender dysphoria. I don't believe people need to actually be diagnosed with gender dysphoria in order to consider themselves or be considered trans, just that they could be diagnosed if they saw the appropriate professional. I do think though that there are a number of ways a person could get gender dysphoria, and I think that the only one that leads to actual satisfaction after transitioning and is the most common one is the brain not matching the biological sex. I feel like that's probably the extent of my beliefs on the issue that you need to know so I'll get started.  To start I'll validate non binary people, so first my significant other is non binary, and they experience gender dysphoria. Their dysphoria fits at least 2 of the diagnostic criteria also they experience the general feeling in the same way I do so they're super valid. They don't feel the need to pass in any way either and why should they? If they like the way they look then they should be allowed to look like that. That goes for binary people too trans or not. Now to be a little less validating I do not think non binary can be viewed as a gender because despite there being a number of possible ways to feel it they all boil down to not purely man and not purely woman, so I consider it to be more of a half gender so hilariously the talk show host wasn't actually entirely wrong in saying there are 2 and a half genders. I think that non binary identities that go beyond simply the term non binary are fine to label oneself with and can make people feel better about themselves but aren't common enough to try to construct gender roles around and shape society towards. So neopronouns seem unreasonable because they/them pronouns are perfectly fine and descriptive.  Next what do I believe defines gender? So I think that gender comes from all three of the things mentioned in the video, it comes from biology, identity or your mind, and society or presentation. I think the least important of the three factors is biology and especially anatomy because that usually doesn't come up or apply in every day life and it's only really used to create the definition of gender and the most basic roles that people fall into. Next presentation or society, I think that that is an important part of gender because what societal roles one takes on largely defines how that person is perceived and their place in society so it is a more functional way to describe gender. Finally there's identity, which I think is the most important because societal roles and biology/anatomy can be changed over time identity cannot, I would feel like I should've been born a woman whether I was born in Ancient Rome, medieval Europe, the modern day Middle East, the far future on some space station, or well right now exactly where I am, it also wouldn't change with anatomy so no matter how I was born and no matter how my body changes there will always be the immutable feeling of female within my mind, I could be a bodiless mind uploaded to the cloud and my gender identity would be the same. Now with that said I think that in transsexual people (I use the word transsexual because I only want to talk about the people with the most intense feelings of gender dysphoria right now) the order or importance actually largely reverses because the most basic instincts of a person include reproductive roles so when your body doesn't fit the reproductive roles that your mind and identity set out for you, you really feel it on the most fundamental level. With society transsexual people feel the need for acceptance and feel the need to be seen as filling the roles that are expected of them as to not be reminded of their biological reality, because the biological reality is incredibly painful and harmful to a trans person's mental well-being, sometimes so much so that people feel the need to fill roles that they would prefer not to just to be accepted. The reason why identity is least important is because it is with you all your life and therefore doesn't feel like it needs to fit anything new it doesn't feel wrong so it doesn't feel important.   So why does this matter? It matters where gender comes from to have 1 the best idea how to fix it and 2 the best idea of your ideas and so are able to actually convince and show other people why they should be accepting of trans people. That's really where my model and opinions come from, convincing other people that trans people are valid and that they should be supportive and accepting, the first part of my model can be used for religious transphobes, the 'science' transphobes can be convinced by using both parts of my model, and the second part of my model can be used for TERFs or gender critical feminists. The model is actually backed up by differences in the brain and how society treats gender, it is also back up by the effectiveness of treatments for gender dysphoria or the outdated gender identity disorder, so I think that the model seems pretty valid.  Anyway that was a lot to write and I don't feel like this comment needs to be any longer so if you have any questions please ask.

Hi Natalie, been following you for a while and I love your videos. Now I have an essay.   You know, despite not really needing an answer, and the fact that we should value people's humanity over putting them in a well defined box, I think I may have an answer for you. I don't know if this helps, but this is how I have always thought of it:   I think if we consider a combination of performance, identity, and biology, we can come to a working theory. It is a well known fact that it is more likely for identical twins to both identify as trans than fraternal twins, (the same goes with being gay). All male fetuses start out female, and many people are born with intersex characteristics. This proves that there is a genetic/biological basis of trans, non-binary, and gay identities.   When it comes to performance theory, people may see how this can exclude people who are gender-non conforming, and suggest that drag-queens are actually women.   But think about it like this: when a drag-queen dresses up, the intent is to 'imitate women,' not be women.   When a trans woman dresses up, she is expressing her womanhood. In both these contexts, doing the same thing, means different things for different people.   Lots of things work like this. In English for example, one word that is harmless could easily be a swear word in another language, and vice versa.   And this can extend to gender non-conformity as well: maybe one person's idea of womanhood is not the same as someone else's. One trans woman may feel that wearing dresses makes her feel feminine, while another may feel like looking like Ellen DeGeneres makes them feel like a woman.   Different things might make different people feel validated in their gender be they non-binary, gender-conforming, and/or non-gender-conforming. It all depends on how they, as individuals, were socialized, who inspires them, and how they feel about their gender. Some people may not see any tangible thing they wear, or do as inherently gendered, and simply have an inner sense of self that is important to them.   Of course, there are plenty of people who are in the closet, and who cannot openly perform and declare their identity. Are they not trans too? This is why we can't have a strict devotion to performance theory. To say that people in closet are not trans, is just as ludicrous as saying that gay people in the closet, are not really gay.   We can conclude then that although performance, and biology are certainly part of being trans, it is not the full story.   What about identification then? Some people may say that identifying as something is not enough.   How do we know we are trans then? Is it because of dysphoria? Is anyone without it just faking? I had to sit down and really think about this one, because it was very relevant to me.   How do I know I am trans if I don't always feel dysphoria?   Figuring out I was trans was a complicated process. And I would say dysphoria, for me at least, didn't start showing up until after I realized that I was. Most of the time I am actually completely comfortable with my body, and I still see myself as a trans person, when I look in the mirror.   Sometimes, when I look at my reflection, or I am laying on my bed, staring at the ceiling, I think about who I am, and how I got here. I look back into my childhood, and I think about how I realized that I liked women. It wasn't because I hated men, but rather, because I just felt an attraction to women. When I came to that realization, I started to realize the different standards we have for gay people, and trans people.   You don't have to have a hatred of men to be called a lesbian, you just have to desire women. And when you consider asexual people, that desire does not have to even be sexual, but more mental/emotional.   But it would be foolish to say for instance: 'Well, if you don't completely feel disgusted by men, (or if you are asexual), you should not become a 'trender lesbian.' You are making real lesbians look bad!' But to be trans, some people want you to prove that you completely hate your body, or you can't transition at all. Why isn't the desire to simply live as a woman/man/other enough?   'Well if they just desire to, and nothing more, doesn't that suggest it is a choice?' I hear you say. However, gay people don't desire the same sex because they choose to, but rather, because they are born that way. In a similar way, perhaps trans people's desire to transition, and/or their sense of self, is not a choice, but rather something inherent to their biology as well. Perhaps the inner sense of self that they feel/discover in regards to their gender, has a biological basis that they did not choose.   I have never met a cis person who had a serious desire/drive to become another gender. Some people may play with gender non-conformity to try, and figure themselves out, but ultimately discover that they are just gnc. Moreover, cases of de-transition are rarer than videos of the US president saying something that makes sense.   So perhaps, the only people who have a serious drive in the first place, and/or an inner sense of self, are people who are trans.   I myself didn't figure out I was trans because I hated my body. I figured it out because something a cross-dresser said in a show resonated with me as a human being. They said, 'I don't care if people see me as a boy or a girl. I want people to recognize me for who I am, rather than what sex I am.'   The gender apathy was not the thing that resonated with me, but rather, the part about being a person, rather than one of two sexes. I realized that is what I am: a person, not necessarily a boy, and not necessarily a girl.   And how do I know who I am? That question can be different for different people. But I will make the question easier by posing a different question: how does someone know they are a poet? You don't necessarily have to be good, and you don't necessarily have to hate other things that you do. You don't mind working at the quite retail store down the corner and your boss is really nice. But it doesn't fulfill you. And that's how you know you are poet: you like doing everything else, but you love and feel complete when you have finished your own epic.   Being myself, makes me feel more complete as a person, (but I still have depression, so even though there is one weight off my shoulders being my authentic self, I still feel like shit, most of the time).   A little cheesy I know, and the analogy is not meant to be taken as a direct comparison to something like sexuality and/or gender identity, (which are persecuted identities, whereas being a poet is a profession), but I hope it helps to get my point across.   So my complete hypothesis is as follows: trans people are people who have a sense of self, that is inherent to their biology, of a different gender than the one they were assigned at birth.  How they transition, (be it socially, and/or physically), is their performance, and is the beginning of their coming out in public life. Dysphoria is the discomfort some trans people may feel as a result of this.

I have a question about one of the points made here about the medical basis for gender dysphoria. One argument was that because Tiffany never saw a picture of her brain, she can't know she has a 'female brain' and that her dysphoria was really valid as a result of her feelings. The issue here I find is that we don't do brain scans for most mental illnesses (using mental illness as an example, don't want to have that debate right now). I have ADHD, Anxiety, and Depression and never got a brain scan for any of them. Mental illnesses are judged by their symptoms because they have predictable effects on how people feel and behave, and we don't need a full scan in order to reliably diagnose them. If it walks like a duck and talks like a duck, we don't need to sequence its genome to reliably predict that it is a duck. I imagine it is much the same with diagnosing dysphoria. Obtaining a medical diagnosis with mental illness is important because we have an inherently skewed view of ourselves, and tend to have heavy biases when it comes to our own emotional state. This is why self-diagnosis is extremely dangerous when it comes to mental illness, and why I cringed a little bit at the insinuation that Tiffany's reliance on professional medicine to treat her dysphoria was using 'a man in a lab coat signing a prescription pad' to feel valid.

while this is about to be a very long comment and not an academic peer-reviewed paper how's this for your scientific explanation: mirror neurons. Those are the braincells that allow us to learn from fellow humans by imitating their behaviour, feeling empathy and understanding abstract concepts that only exist in language and not in the physical world. When parents teach children manners, or when a kid tries to emulate their favourite superhero or character, the human tendency to divide each other as in-group/out-group, those are all behaviours that help build in individual identity that also relates to the world around them, it's a thing that definitely doesn't stop when we reach adulthood, aligning ourselves with peers who feel are similar to ourselves or represent ideas we agree with is the building block of society. Gender as a social construct is one of the many ways we communicate our inner self to the world around us, leaving aside the performative theory that deals more with the mind-body problem, genders are social roles (gender roles are the generalization of this) that encompass traits one feels align with the self and likens the self to others, there are people who have a tendency to take care of others, the friend mom they're called, which is an unnecessary imposition of gender to a trait that is likely to be encountered in mothers but that oesn't mean other people can't be nurturing as well, we are all aware that not all mothers embody the charecteristic that make someone ''motherly'', seeing other people being caring and wanting to be like that too, it's an aspiration to a certain role in society. Any personality trait that has social consequences, like leadership or compassion or humor,  any one individual can have a bunch of these and recognize in their surroundings who is like them and who is unlike them, gender in society has more to do with who you relate to, all the unique combinations of variables that construct a person can exist without gender, the tendency of certain traits clumping together by the bunch makes the group unified through them seem like a clear type of person but that mix is more correlation than causation. If fathers really didn't have a single nurturing bone in their bodies whichever statistically outlier moms that were not caring wouldn't have succeded at raising babies and perpetuating their genes, but it wasn't so, as has been pointed out by science before humans and society have consequences on our species that go beyond the most logically convenient actions, graves in cultures areoung the world prove that disabled people were taken care of by their tribes far into their lives despite being ''of no use to the survival of the group'', because humans form bonds among them, as long as the sentient mind can distinguish between the self and the other, there will be groups of people united by similarities, and transness is easily one of those cases, where sometimes what happens first is feeling otherness where you're being told there's similarity, some people who wear glasses are not super smart some people who do time-consuming art have a short-fuse when people anger them, people who are very socially active can be generally disliked; simply put one single trait in a person, whether they form groups based on it or not, is ultimately insufficient to understanding them as a whole, and the binary proposes absolutes that don't respond to the actual complexity of the human mind and experience.

So, I am one of those truscum'ers.   Yes, I believe that transsexualism is a category and therefore has definable characteristics which then must exclude; but it doesn't then make the excluded invalid in regards to what ever category they fall into. I don't think it's then ok to be an ass-hat to gender-queer people; most of which are focused on social gender things, which are rather flexible, so it's not unreasonable by any means. I simply see them being in different categories, with some shared aspects. We have a common thing tho, which is that once upon a time, there was zero way of physically transitioning, and the only thing one could do was use social aspects of gender... which seems to account for other cultures 3rd genders; it's not like trans people were accepted as women/men back then. Many trans-people do feel mocked, that someone who is 'happy' with their body, but doesn't want to be femme (dresses/acts less stereotypically girl) has equal claim to 'the trans identity'... which leads us to: Gender-dysphoria, perhaps the main reason, but it's not as simple as that. Gender-dysphoria is not exclusive to trans people: in youth it can manifest from one's difficulty navigating gender/sexuality (60-90% desistance rates, which is from about 11 papers on the subject) to someone being abused. Basically, having GD doesn't automatically make you trans (which is part of a larger conversation). I no longer experience gender dysphoria... and I am still very much trans. Yes, I have had SRS, and obviously take hormones. So what is GD to a transsexual girl? Well, I can anecdotally describe my own experience (along with conversations I have had with dozens of trans women and men). GD is defined as being both in relation to one's body and social, which holds up...but I don't think they are equal from my own exp (along with others). Being socially recognized is great, but when you are naked and alone, you still have GD... despite being called miss all day. I was rather 'passing' before HRT, so I got lots of social validation... but it never made up for how I felt in relation to my body, even how testosterone made me feel (which was anxious, so very anxious from puberty to transitioning, because I felt 'off' a few months into HRT, poof gone, when I had to stop HRT and my T lvs when up, poof same feelings).  Now, you can say 'it's a medical construct' and modern therefore it's 'the trend' or it's the first time in history that trans-people has a way to actually manifest themselves fully. Before I knew what gender dysphoria was, along with being trans... I felt like a girl, having a penis seemed extremely weird, and when I hit puberty I found myself in descending into hell.  Yes, I love my transmedialismnesss; I feel like I am very lucky to exist at this point in time where I am able to see myself fully, rather than being trapped in hell.  Now, the idea of right brain, wrong body was dismissed.. casually, without real evidence... that that was a rather weak point. No one has seen their chromosomes, how do they even know they are XX or XY? OMG! *mind blown*.  There are studies to that point this this theory as being a possibility. The larger proof of theory are intersex people. Unfortunately many people with this condition have been coin flipped, and it was wrong.. the positive is that it does show that an individual cannot just be force gendered into being a 'girl' or a 'boy', there is something innate, or else no intersex person would have transitioned (trans people also reinforce this). Which kinda leads to transsexualism being most likely a type of (or strongly related to) intersex, either genetic or developmental.   Yes, trans people often want a bedrock to their identity, because it's stronger than I feels this way. But, really the argument against us is a biological one, and it's forced on us that I need to have the most empirically sound reasoning for my existence. Yes, gay people are not required to have a biological reasoning, but well.... being gay is rather obvious, and the proof is that you are a girl who only likes girls or a boy that only likes boys. Being trans seems rather nebulous to many people; or to the other extreme that biology is being ignored aka science denial. I fulfill most of the social aspects of being a girl, while not being a complete biological girl, but to our best knowledge it most likely I do have a biological reason of why I am this way. I am not a girl in a proper sense  (not Plato's ideal form by any means), I am the perfectly imperfect type, born from the messiness that can arise from biology. I've read a little bit (and with a little bit, I mean a *little* bit) about third genders in non-western cultures, and I often felt that for many of these people, if they were born in 'the West', they would've probably felt reasonably at home in a binary trans framework.  But the thing is, they weren't born in the West, and they grew up with a cultural framework that explained the same -or very similar feelings- in a different way. A way that they now probably feel more comfortable with, since that's what they grew up with.  People like Tiffany try so hard to strictly define gender. To describe and catalogue it, and put it in a nice rigid box that is the same for everyone across the world, but I don't think it works that way. Personally, I get the idea that, while the feelings (for lack of a better word) underlying gender dysphoria and transgenderism are probably the same across cultures, the way these feelings are expressed, and how they take shape is probably strongly influenced by cultural factors.  This is kind of how I see the current emergence of non-binary genders too. Maybe a lot of enby people would have been comfortable as cis or binary trans people in another time, or another cultural framework. Maybe they would've been able to express their gender by being gender non-conforming or doing drag or having a fetish, without attaching a trans identity to it. Or maybe not? Either way, the cultural framework is shifting to one that allows for that ambiguity. It's a new 'shape' to pour those feelings in, and I honestly think it is only a matter of time before this shape becomes as embedded in our culture as third genders are in their respective cultures. It's a cultural change and I don't think it's a bad one. In fact, I think it's pretty cool. And hell, maybe one day it will shift again, and all the future people will think we're idiots.

I think one of the key tensions here is a... well, western desire for reductionism. If we can appeal to some form methodology that relies on a positivist, mechanistic certainty, it's intuitively easier to swallow. A -> B therefore C. The problem is this type of metaphysics often leads to the type of exclusion and bigotry displayed here. The notion that the world and by extension biology are fixed, pregiven and linear, and any deviation from that model is the result of our own epistemic limitations rather than an underlying fluidity or reciprocal relational metaphysics is a staple of American culture. Personally I feel an approach that ontologises epistemology, or has a more methodological individualism at it's center empowers and legitimizes the lived experiences of many oppressed groups, and liberates everyone else from those stringent, realist structures they force themselves to adhere to, often becoming a detriment to themselves and others. Anyway, great video and it was nice to hear Judith Butler invoked!

Trans-medicalism is just trash at the end if you game it out... it's no different from saying people with penises can't be women. Do you really think there is enough of a difference between cishet, gay, transgender, etc. brains that you would be able with enough technology to scan brains and be able to consistently and perfectly tell the difference between brains? What if someone who claims to be totally queer gets their brain scanned and comes up cishet? Do we accuse them of lying, of trying to sneak into women's bathrooms?     Being transgender is not some clear physical hardwire in your brain, nor is it a purely performative act in a social construct, nor is it a spiritual soul-shift. Its people who live in a specific culture with a specific history and specific language being uncomfortable with that specific culture's proscribed gender role for them. If they feel uncomfortable but can't perform it for whatever reason, then they are still transgender. If they are simply dabbling in it because its trendy and they like campy fashion, then they become transgender as soon as they decide that they are less comfortable more comfortable with those proscribed roles. The real philosophical question comes when there is no proscribed roles, one could claim the very idea of transgender in such a world would be obsolete.

I kinda miss hearing the actual argument? Rather than this weird condescending strawman sketch?   I think the topic is interesting though. We have gender dysphoria, a psychological concept that has received testing and has gotten a good portion of scientific backing. It is a (relatively) observable symptom, as in you can do similar tests as you do for depression. And no, we do not see the brain to test for either, because frankly, the tech/science isn't there yet. It doesn't mean we can't (approximate) a psychological diagnosis of both. This indirectly observable symptom, when present, clearly indicates that a person is trans. Or depressed. But yes. That leads to a diagnosis, treatment, and a good way to formalize it all. We can say with relatively confidence that trans people exist, and are not simply strongly believing something to be true.   The same is not necessarily true for non-binary people. Now, to be fair, the science isn't in yet there what so ever. They might be proven to exist as well. Assuming that they're relatively proven to not exist, they're still not hurting anyone by dressing up in whatever way they want. I mean, it wouldn't make sense to subsidize surgery, but beyond that, let them live their life to the fullest. I mean, having to use 'they/them' is probably pretty annoying to sound out in replacement of the relatively quick he/she, but besides that, I'm on board. Just because they believe in something that doesn't exist, doesn't mean it's hurtful. It's an identity, like a national identity, which fills people's life with meaning. And if they're proven to exist over the next couple of years or decades, then that's all the better.   My main point is that there is a distinction to be made between that which exists, and that which we identify as. The reason you can't ignore being trans is because it exists. Even if you will it away and never really knew it was a thing, it'll be a thing. If non-binary exists, the same should be the case there - haunting you even when you look away. Meanwhile, while we may feel strongly with what we identify with (ie: nationality), if we didn't want to identify with it from one moment to the next, we would simply be able to change our identity at a whim (Perhaps including some emotional outburst, but yeah). That doesn't make the identity wrong or evil, however - it's a valid expression of our personality like any other expression.   So yeah, I agree with none and all of the weird strawmen in that show. I guess that's what centrism does to yah, eh?

I have to wonder, why is there this need for 'social policing'? And furthermore, why is it so mainstream in our current society? Gender and orientation can be important on a personal and close interpersonal level... but in the big picture it is irrelevant. At least from my perspective. I functionally don't care what gender or orientation some person is that I don't know -- and even of the people I know, it doesn't matter (in regard to being able to communicate with them) we get into the question of 'do I want to have a sexual interaction with this person?' as well as 'who am I?'       Why is so much energy spent, on the level of _The Public,_ trying to minimize or de-legitimize or even outlaw anything that strays even a little bit from 'the standard' setup our current society has certified as ... standard?       There must be some connection to power. Some need to maintain a given status quo or given mindset so that those with power can maintain it. That's the only motivation that makes sense to me... and yet still this resistance to 'some people are different' makes no sense. I don't think capitalism cares... no directly. Rather, it's the folks who are trained by religion and social norms derived from religion who care so greatly that they will collectively revolt from the capitalist reigns if those who are 'different' are accepted. Okay... so that gives the motivation for the capitalists enforcing (and reinforcing) this needless opposition and cruelty. But what of 'religion' of which we all know we're talking about Abrahamic religion in particular (Christy, Muslimy, Ortho-J), and even then not all adherents. Mostly it's those who have _use_ of their religion not for personal beliefs or self improvement reasons... but as a tool for asserting authority over others. And now it clicks together for me. It's not really an issue with religion, but with those seeking power over others and just using religion as a rather convenient tool. And one way to implement that power is to have people 'join your side' against a threat. So it's helpful to find and label threats, because if everything is fine and there are no threats, people stop bothering doing as you say because... well, everything's fine and they don't need you to guide them. And obviously you can't point to the corporations, wealthy elites, and the capitalist system in general as a threat because that's a large part of how you build and maintain your power. So it helps to find 'fringe' groups, minorities, to point out as a threat. They won't be able to provide a meaningful counter attack because they are few in number and if you can keep the pressure on, they also will be kept at a disadvantage within capitalism. Keep them ostracized, engender mistrust of them among those you 'lead' and never forget to paint them as a threat. Because again, if there isn't a threat to unite against, your followers will disperse over time or come up with their own ideas you can't use as leverage.       Naturally this means there's a part of society that is kept relatively isolated and off balance. They have questions like 'what the hell is gender, even?' They might wonder 'why are certain shapes or colors of clothes not allowed to be worn by some kinds of people?' 'Why does it matter which two people decide to kiss or love each other?' 'Why does it matter how that person looks?' 'Why does it matter what body language another person adopts?'       Among the 'I'm just asking questions' crowd, there are certain questions they don't want anyone to ask. They certainly don't like genuine and open questions, either. They far prefer leading questions... that lead where they want. To maintain a status quo with them holding much if not all of the power.  =.=.=.=.=.=.=.=.=.=.=.=.=.=.=.=.=.=.= Love your videos, Natalie. They always get me thinking. Also, when Jackie struggled with opening the popsicle I genuinely laughed, it was some unexpected comedy. One critique? The 'digital messiah' was a bit difficult to understand. The voice mixed with a bit with the synth music at points. But maybe I just don't have the best hearing.

I did not sit down at age four and decide on my gender. Did anyone here? No?  Look at language. If born in China of the fifth century I would be speaking a dialect of Chinese. Perhaps gender expression is not hard wired as language yet sexual dimorphism is there as is attachment to bio males or females in early development. The camera angle technique is really interesting; notice how Tiffany is always facing at a slight angle away from the viewer when she's talking to Baltimore, but Baltimore is always facing directly at the camera, toward us, when speaking to Tiffany. It gives the impression that B. has a more direct line of communication to the viewer, like a kind of 4th wall teasing as a means of more effectively getting the message across. But because the conversation is still primarily between two fictional characters within the video, Tiffany still acts as a sort of proxy so the viewer can be more at ease when listening, they feel less 'talked at' and are thus more likely to remain less defensive, and more receptive, to the message Natalie is attempting to convey. Not sure if it's intentional but it's cool nonetheless. Two-spirit is more in line with other 'almost transgender but not at all' things in other Asiatic cultures.  Personally... I was around at the turn of the century when it became 'hip' to be gay. I can't tell you how often I was introduced as X's gay best friend for the other person to respond with 'Oh, you're gay? Well I'm bisexual, but I would never have sex with a same-sex person.' To which I was like.... 'Then you're not bi, stop coopting my sexuality to make yourself not milquetoast' in my head. And sure enough, *none* of those 'bisexuals' are anything but heteronormative heterosexuals today. Which damages the rest of us as it gives 'evidence' for how it's just a choice. (It's not.) So I worry when I see people claiming trans identity *while also claiming cisgender everything* (presentation, pronouns, etc) that history is repeating and these individuals are doing systemic harm by giving ammo to people who will try and claim transgender is a choice or a phase.  Though I would never confront someone over it. I just worry about the others they may be unintentionally, indirectly harming.

I'm only halfway through this video and I will be watching the whole thing, but I have to say that I still somewhat disagree with the message I've seen so far. The LGBT community gained equality by explaining to bigoted people that you do not choose to be gay, lesbian, etc. Trans/non-binary people with dysphoria are included in this because they do not choose to be trans, it's an inherent part of them that they were born with. It's difficult for me to associate so called 'trans-trenders' with the community when they do not have dysphoria, because this implies that they do not have the innate medical need to transition. I'm not asking this question to be disrespectful and people are welcome to explain this better to me, but if you are trans or identify as any other gender without having dysphoria, is it a choice?  Edit: Another point that I sometimes have an issue with is that some people tend to confuse gender identity with gender expression. For example, if a man wants to wear traditionally female things like dresses, makeup, have long hair, etc it doesn't necessarily make him any less of a man. These attributes of gender are socially constructed, so they inherently cannot define your identity. They define your style and expression. In our society, a trans woman would most likely want to wear dresses and makeup to 'pass' as a woman, but in an ideal setting, these style characteristics shouldn't be defining her identity. Imagine a society where traditional gender expression was swapped, i.e. men historically wore dresses and women traditionally buzzed their hair or something. A trans woman would still have the brain chemistry of a woman, but she would present entirely different in our society. I hope I haven't made this too confusing, but what I'm basically trying to say is that just because a person wants glitter in their beard, long hair, makeup, as dresses, it doesn't necessarily make them some sort of new gender, it just makes them unique in their expression.

As a (as far as i can tell) cis girl who's learned about gender largely from your videos and various people on tumblr, the concept of identifying as a gender is still really blurry when it comes to the technicalities, and the discussion in the second part of this video really summed up the problem nicely. If we take gender to be entirely biological and based on chromosomes or the genitalia you're born with, like terfs insist, we end up completely invalidating trans people's experiences with gender dysphoria and identity as either confusion or lying, which isn't very accurate. If we take the transmed idea that gender is biological, but tied to your brain rather than your chromosomes, we end up invalidating the experiences of both trans and cis people whose brains don't match up with their identity. If we go with gender as a set of performative behaviours, we end up invalidating the experiences of gender nonconforming people, closeted trans people etc., which is why your earlier videos on the topic kept bothering me. I suppose Tabby's solution really is the one that makes the most sense for the time being and we should just respect people's identities, no matter how ridiculous or nonsensical they may seem to us, personally. I guess I don't really have anything meaningful to say on the matter, just that I'm grateful you addressed this issue directly, because otherwise i'd still be stuck in my own head wondering which option made the most sense. But the science is just not conclusive that men and women have inherently different brains.  'One of the authors, Daphna Joel, had previously published a study of structures and connections in over 1,400 brains from men and women aged between 13 and 85, in which no evidence was found of two distinct groups of brains that could be described as either typically male or typically female. Brains were more typically unique 'mosaics' of different features - something more correctly characterised as a single heterogeneous population.  Such a mosaic of features cannot be explained in purely biological terms; it is a measure of the effect of external factors. This is true even at the most fundamental level. For example, it can be shown that a 'characteristically male' density of dendritic spines or branches of a nerve cell can be changed to the 'female' form simply by the application of a mild external stress. Biological sex alone cannot explain brain differences; to do so requires an understanding of how, when and to what extent external events affect the structure of the brain.  The notion that our brains are plastic or malleable and, crucially, remain so throughout our lives is one of the key breakthroughs of the last 40 years in our understanding of the brain. Different short- and long-term experiences will change the brain's structure. It has also been shown that social attitudes and expectations such as stereotypes can change how your brain processes information. Supposedly brain-based differences in behavioural characteristics and cognitive skills change across time, place and culture due to the different external factors experienced, such as access to education, financial independence, even diet.' I'm almost 9 minutes in, and first off I want to say: Yes, I think being trans is indeed a medical condition. I wouldn't call it a psychiatric condition because it's not like having a male or female brain is a medical condition, but it's certainly a medical one--misalignment of the brain with the rest of the body. There is some research that says that male and female brains have different proportions of white and grey matter, but it's still a very contentious topic in neuroscience, a field which we still know very little about (I hope the rest of the video has some insights from your history as a sort-of neuroscientist, I've been waiting to hear your take on that for _ages_ now...). Non-binary people, by this logic, have brains that are in an intermediate state--essentially being intersex but in the brain. Now, dysphoria can be very, very real, but it can stem from things other than brain misalignment--e.g. a form of depression or self-loathing or other kinds of psychiatric disorder, as evidenced by the experiences of people detransitioning. When Baltimore asked Tiffany if she'd gotten her brain scanned, it just made me think about how I've been thinking for years now that people really _should_ get their brain scanned, so that doctors can see whether it's an issue of brain misalignment, or just the manifestation of a different underlying issue that should be addressed differently; otherwise, patients could go through years of taking hormones, sterilizing themselves and damaging their kidneys (if they're taking oestrogen and spiro--not sure about the side effects of testosterone and whatever the male equivalent of spiro is), and spending loads of money on a series of painful surgeries with long recovery periods, and failing to resolve the _actual_ underlying issue that just stays there and fucks everything up again once more. (P.S.: Please, Natalie, I've been waiting for months for you to approve my Hebrew translations, there are a bunch of at risk teens I really want to show them to)

HOLY SHIT IVE BEEN WAITING FOR A VIDEO ABOUT THIS TOPIC FOREVER!!! I LOVE YOU,,,  Honestly, the whole dysphoria debate made me repress any question I had about my gender identity. I was afraid to experiment with my gender for fear that I'd be seen as a 'trender'. I read countless posts about what makes a trans person valid and what makes them invalid, and I internalized it all. I thought I was too comfortable to be trans, but, in reality, I'd been so uncomfortable throughout my life that it became the norm; it became my comfort. My discomfort is real, but it's not the cookie-cutter suffering that every 15 year old transmed on tumblr vents about. I didn't know what I was feeling was dysphoria, and, therefore, assumed that I didn't have dysphoria; I assumed I couldn't be trans. It wasn't until I stopped giving a fuck about whether or not I was a 'valid' trans person that I was FINALLY about to discover myself. I am proud to call myself a trans man, especially considering how much of my life I spent trying to fight that label.  Even if I didn't have dysphoria, I would still be trans. My pain does not define me, and to hear people scream that it is the most integral part of my identity is defeating.
